deck_name: The Winged Dragon of Ra OTK (Genesys)
deck_description: a deck totally focused on going second

Ghoti has been a fan favorite of many people since release, including me, however, it has never had the chance to actually be meta relevant. Well, this changes now, in the lower power format that is Genesys the fish migth actually be good enough. Not only is the base deck 0 points, with the only mandatory card that costs anything being Dragite, but taking advantage that not many handtraps fill the format by going all out and being able to play some of the best handtraps themselves.

This version of the deck is better going second, but the side deck has some blowout that can win the game if you want to go first in games 2 and 3. More specifically the interaction between Stealh Kragen and Virtue Stream. Depending on the deck your facing that by it self can win the game.

Tested deck in-house tournaments with up to 16 players. It was tested in over 5 of these and performed incredibly well, consistently ranking in the top 4 each time. Have fun with it. I'm not sure if I want to play 3 Awakening Forests, so I'd love some input. The math says I don't need it, but I love seeing the card. 

Siding:

Revival golem and Gravekeepers trap are sided in going first for the two pankertops.

Aluber the Jester of Despia searches for Despia, Theater of the Branded. Theater of the Branded can fusion summon a level 8 or higher fusion monster by using the monsters in your hand or field as material.

Aluber + any light or dark Shaddoll monster = Masquerade the Blazing Dragon or Despian Quaeritis

Like Theater of the Branded, Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous can fusion summon a level 8 or higher fusion monster by using the monsters in your hand or field as material.

Blazing Cartesia + any Shaddoll monster = El Shaddoll Construct

Blazing Cartesia + any light or dark Shaddoll monster = Granguignol the Dusk Dragon

Granguignol can send El Shaddoll Apkallone from the extra deck to the graveyard to search for or recover a Shaddoll card, then discard 1 card.

deck_excerpt: Gotta catch 'em all! Legendaries at least!
deck_description:
I will refer to each as their pokemon counterpart only, not sorry. 

Kyoro = Groudon | Kairo = Kyogre | Genro = Rayquaza | Tensei = Giratina | Sosei = Arceus

- The moment you get Arceus, Melody, or Rising in your hand, you're basically set to board spam everything, assuming your opponent cannot stop you.
- Remember that the full potential of War Zone is only when Arceus is faced up on top of the extra deck to get everything rolling.
- Giratina is a stupid card to have in your pendulum zone negating anything that would touch your Pokemon spells. 
- Kyogre will continuously be dumped into the grave, Rayquaza will be chillin in the banished pile, and Groudon will be abused between the deck and your cand constantly. 
- Varudras is your ultimate ace in the hole against anything dumb coming your way. 
- The continuous spells are indeed useful when needed, but remember when to sack any of your pokemon cards for them. 
- Super Poly is self-explanatory, board-breaking little pest it is. 
- Superdreadnoughts are literally an OHKO if you get the combo off
- Assortment of fusions I found useful while playing the deck for Super Poly fodder, change them as you see fit! 
- Fuwalos can be swapped for Maxx C, I just don't have one IRL to utilize to the fullest. 

Hope you enjoy a pure pokemon deck! Other fun ways to incorporate them are a DInomorphia/Pokemon split with them, or a Jurrac/Pokemon Stun deck.

deck_excerpt: Goblin Bikers deck for Rivalry of Warlords 2025 format.
deck_description: Goblin Bikers deck for Rivalry of Warlords 2025 format.

Trying out the new Genesys format with and old favorite.

The jank of the jank lives and breathes in my veins and I'm here to give it to you.

Wanna make Cyberdark End go "brrrr"? well you can do that. That's the standard combo for the deck.

Alternatively you can go into a XYZ combo and grab out your Infinity and King Regulus for a double omni-negate setup.

You can also go through a small Nova/Infinity combo into Stardust Synchron to cheat away 5 cards from the top of your deck with Chaos Ruler and then turn him into Shooting Majestic Star for a second approach at a double omni-negate setup.

Bust some boards with Eltanin or Clockwok Night.

Nearly every combo in this deck is searchable through 4 different starters (Core, Claw, Emergency, Horizon).


This deck is designed to go First or Second. Though preferrably First with the majority of the combo power relying on setting up a "nope" board.

Play the classic Cyber Dragon archetype with a new spin to it's internal struucture.

deck_excerpt: A opportunity to test the possibilities capable with the Killer Tune engine.
deck_description:
Synopsys: A Killer Tune focused deck that utalizes a Psychic engine to support it's first turn plays, with PSY-Frame and Brain Controller to help boost it's going secound capability.

Main Line Combo:

Combo: "Killer Tune Cue"

(Going First: Normal Line)

  • {Only If you start with "Synchro Overtake"}
    • Use "Synchro Overtake" to SS "K.Tune Mix"
    • "K.Tune Mix" effect to Search "K.Tune Cue"
  • NS "K.Tune Cue" Use it's on summon abbility to SS "Red Nova"
  • Synchro "K.Tune Track" using "K.Tune Cue" + "Red Nova"
    • CL1: "K.Tune Track" CL2: "Red Nova" CL3: "K.Tune Cue"
      • Resolve CL3:  how ever you wish
      • Resolve CL2: SS "K.Tune Reco"
      • Resolve CL1: Search "Juke Joint"
  • On Summon effect of "K.Tune Reco" Search "K.Tune Clip"
  • Place "Juke Joint" on field and activate "Juke Joint" effect
    • Send "K.Tune Track" and then SS "K.Tune Mix"
      • (If you started the line with "Syncro Overtake" Send "K.Tune Track" To SS "K.Tune Cue" instead Then Ignore the next bullet point)
    • "K.Tune Mix" effect Search "K.Tune Cue"
  • Synchro "K.Tune Remix" using "K.Tune Mix" + "K.Tune Cue"
  • Synchro "K.Tune Red Seal" using "K.Tune Reco" + "K.Tune Clip"

Synopsis: This is the line that you will most likely be going into a majority of the time. It ends on multiple interactions as well as follow up for the next turn. This line also leaves you with an extra normal summon off of "Juke Joint" so if you were to draw Mind Procedure or Brain Controller you can use them as extenders to either set up more disruption on you're opponents turn or breakers for your next turn.

(Going First: Normal Line + Mind Procedure)

  • Do the Normal Line to completion without using "Juke Joint" secound NS.
    • NS "Mind Procedure" use effect to Search "Teleport Fusion"
    • Set "Teleport Fusion"
  • End Turn

(Opponents Turn)

  • At the most opertune time activate "K.Tune Remix" Target "K.Tune Mix" + "K.Tune Clip"
    • Add "K.Tune Clip" to hand then SS "K.Tune Mix"
    • Synchro summon "Silent PSY Magician" using "Mind Procedure" + "K.Tune Mix"
  • Activate "K.Tune Clip" To SS itself the Syncro Summon
  • Syncro Summon "Shooting Riser Dragon" using "Silent PSY Magician" + "K.Tune Clip"
    • CL1:"K.Tune Clip" CH2:"Shooting Riser Dragon CL3: "Teleport Fusion"
      • Resolve CL3: SS "Axon Kicker Oracle"
      • Resolve CL2:  Reccomend you Send "Mind Controller" or "Effect Veiler" to the grave from deck but you can send any lvl you want depending on what you whish to end on.
        • You can also chose not to activate "Shooting Riser Dragon" if you wish to Synchro into Level 10's instead
      • Resolve CL1: Banish from Extra deck
  • On banish activation of "Mine Procedure" to SS itself to field
  • Activate "Shooting Riser Dragon"  to Synchro Summon the monster based what you chose to mill with "Shooting Riser Dragon" using "Shooting Riser Dragon" + "Mine Procedure" (Not all cards included in deck list just options that you can go into) 
    • lv7: "F.A Dawn Dragster", "Black Rose Dragon/Moonlight", "Clear Wing", "PSY - Framelord Zeta"
    • lv8: "Accel Synchro", "Crystal Wing", "Berserker of the Tenyi", " PSY - Framelord Omega"
    • lv9: "VW - Shenshen", "Navy Dragon Mech", 
    • lv10: "Chaos Angle", "Chengying", "Shooting Star Dragon"

Synopsis:This line is allows for more felxability with your Endboard and extradeck. Depending on how you choose to build your extra deck you have a multitude of ways to fill in any holes that you might find with your end board. The main down side this has is that if you wish to shotgun the end board you will lose on some interactions that you could have goten from your Killer Tune Cards. 

(Going Secound: Brain Control Line)

  • NS "K.Tune Cue" Use it's on summon abbility to SS "Brain Controller"
    • On Summon use "Brain Controller" to search "Brain Control"
  • Synchro "K.Tune Track" using "K.Tune Cue" + "Brain Controller"
    • CL1: "K.Tune Track" CL2: "K.Tune Cue" CL3: "Brain Controller
      • Resolve: CL2 and CL3 how ever you wish
      • Resolve: CL1 "K.Tune Track" Search"Juke Joint"
  • Place "Juke Joint" on field and activate "Juke Joint" effect
    • Send "K.Tune Track" Summon "K.Tune Mix" 
    • "K.Tune Mix" effect Search "K.Tune Reco"
    • NS "K.Tune Reco" Search "K.Tune Clip"
  • Synchro "K.Tune Red Seal" Using "K.Tune Mix" + "K.Tune Reco"

Synopsis: This line is better going secound as you keep all the main interactions that you would have if you did the Red Nova line but also get to add Brain Control to take an opponents monster. This line also incentives going into early "K.Tune Loudness War" To gain the Attack Bonus off the field spell as Brain Controller gets summoned to the opponents field if used for a synchro summon.

This line can also be used for going first if as in exchange for the extra Distruption that you would get through the "Red Nova" line by summoning "Brain Controller" on the opponents field you now have protection against board breakers like; "Infinite Impermance", "Lightning Storm" and "Evenly Matched" and even the prevent your opponent from using the "Mulcahrmys" during their turn.

 

Pros and Cons

(Pro's)

  • The Deck has a Lot of room for HandTraps/non engine
  • Can play very low to the ground through hand traps and board breakers
  • "Brain Control" gives going secound a searchable Board Breaker.
  • "Mind Procedure" allows for a higher cealing and flexability on what the deck can accomplish
  •  A lot of the lines have built in Chain Blocking so you don't need to wory about certain hand traps.
  • Can use Hand traps as both Interuption and as extenders making duplicate draws less frustrating
  • Turn Zero plays

(Con's)

  • Weak to all of the Mulcharmy's as the deck SS from Hand, Deck and Grave multiple times on both turns make it so that they are always online.
  • "Mind Procedure" Lines are slow and easy to disrupt
  • If you dont have access to NS "K.Tune Cue" or if they prevent the SS you're end board is signifigantly weaker
  • The Tuner lock while not detrimental to the game plan dose limit you're synergies and going first plays.
  • dose not have a way to counter Nibiru before the 5th summon
  • Cannot use and is suseptible to the Dominus traps
  • Engine dose not have a consistent way to search it's in archtype trap and quick play without hard drawing them.

Conclusion

Overall Killer Tune is a strong deck with a cohesive game plan that allows it to play going first or secound with little issues. It's ability to use Hand Traps both as disruption and as extenders makes them always playable even if their activation conditons are unavailable. The inherent locks in the deck do limit what engines you can use but can be easly cirumvented and the ability to play low to the ground makes it so that your never in a situation where you're not playing. But it dose have a hard time playing into or arround alot of the current best HandTraps: Mulcharmy's, Nibiru and the Dominus Traps give the deck very clear choke points that can be exploited.

deck_excerpt: Phryxul is the perfect missing link to combine Branded and Dracotail!
deck_description:
Phryxul is the perfect card to bridge both Branded and Dracotail decks! Before Phryxul's release from DOOD, the Branded Dracotail player would be forced instead to go to Lubellion by sending Mululu and Albaz, which may search a Dracotail spell/trap, but neglects searching for a Branded spell/trap because of the lack of Albion. Forget Phryxul's effects for a second, her most important characteristic is her attribute - LIGHT! This allows Branded Fusion to fusion summon Albion using Phyxul and Albaz, allowing you to simultanously search a Dracotail spell/trap and a Branded spell/trap during the End Phase (aka Main Phase 3 for Branded players)!

As a result, Branded Dracotail is now a much more synergistic fusion of both archetypes! This strategy generates a ton of massive beatsticks on field, smashes through established boards with in-engine cards, and generates a ton of advantage! Albax and Phryxul has truly made the ultimate fusion strategy!

GLHF Duelists! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_excerpt: This deck takes advantage of the lower power format of Genesys to play a full-power Shining Sarcophagus deck.
deck_description:
This deck takes advantage of the lower power format of Genesys to play a full-power Shining Sarcophagus deck. 
The deck prioritizes getting the main card, Sarcophagus, on the field. If you open no Sarcophagus or Gadget Trio, but have Dark Magician Girl or Future Silence, resolve these so you can special summon Dark Magician Girl. Then you can play Shining Sarcophagus. From there, you summon Dark Magician of Destruction to search your Dark Magician. This gives a consistent line for using your Dragon's Mind.
The Pot of Greed and Upstart Goblin allow the deck to run at 35 cards with 12 starters. Shining's greatest weakness is not getting enough starters in your opening hand. (You need about 1 per negate your opponent has on resolution.)


Other Tips: Keep Super poly in your hand if you go first, and have a good opening, then use it during your own next draw phase to out there board if they comboed off.


Cards to replace: (These are the weakest cards in the deck and ones I'm considering removing for something else)
     Quaking Mirror Force (Powerful when combined with Gandora, but very slow)
     Widow Anchor (Only works if you have no field)
     Angel Statue (Predictable and adds very little value if you go 2nd or don't draw it in your opening hand)
     2nd Gandora (The deck only needs one, but 2nd does come up sometimes for fusions and discard fodder)

deck_excerpt: Blue eyes genesys primite Blue-Eyes genesys format
Infamous ritual archetypes join forces in this powerful combo deck with control tendencies
deck_description:
This deck uses the power of generic ritual cards, such as the Impcantations, the "Rites" spells, as well as ASHLAN U1000, a recent TCG exclusive Link 2. It requires 2 monsters with different types and attributes, and says once per turn (hopt) you can reveal 1 Ritual Monster in your hand; add, from your deck to your hand, 1 Ritual Monster with a different Type and Attribute.

So this means that you can do the following: normal summon Gishki Grimness, special summon Gishki Abyss from deck, add Gishki Vision from deck to hand, discard vision to add Evigishki Neremanas from deck to hand, then link summon Salamangreat Almiraj using gishki grimness (600 ATK), then link summon ASHLAN U1000 using Almiraj and Gishki Abyss. From here, simply reveal Neremanas to add Ame no Habakuri no Mitsurugi from deck to hand.

The doorways ASHLAN U1000 opens up from a deckbuilding perspective for Ritual decks is really mindblowing. Here we have a link 2 that can be summoned in almost any ritual deck, and thrives off the combination of different archetypes due to their inherently different typing and attributes.

The impcantations offer surprising flexibility. Take Impcantation Chalislime, a card that mimics Habakuri's special ability that lets you reveal itself to summon a monster that tutors another card. It can now be used as a one-card combo enable due to the fact that it can summon talismandra, letting you directly add Habakuri from deck to hand. Evigishki Gustkraken is your main target when using the Impcantation Inception, the archetypes built in ritual spell. The impcantations ability to set up 2 successive ritual summons with any level 6 or lower ritual monster works perfectly with Gustkraken, easily allowing you to rip 2 cards from the opponents hand before/after almost any section of this combo. From there, you can overlay into an M7 to retrieve any monster from the graveyard, including any monster discarded by chalislime to activate its effect in the first place.

To be able to use a a ritual package like the impcantations but then also have the ability to bypass their use if necessary is absurd, and with 20 one card starters, only 7 of them actually requiring your normal summon, the deck features excellent flexibilty and starting power. The mitsurugi engine turns each chalislime, preparation of rites, focused aquamirror or gishki grimness into Mitsurugi Habakuri access, a strong upside to the investment.

None of this would matter if we didn't have an ace in the hole, a way to bottleneck all incoming decks from defeating your board. Mitsurugi already produced flexible, deep end boards that could navigate around opponents interruption. Now, with the addition of ASHLAN U1000 into almost every combo situation, we now have a way to consistently summon Spright Sprind. This lets us send Mirror Mage of the Ice Barrier from deck to graveyard, conveniently setting up a Rank 2 summon of Gigantic Spright using Spright Sprind and Mirror Mage. This of course gives you access to your Gishki Grimness from the deck, but it also gives you access to another important Level 2 Monster: Knightmare Corruptor Iblee.

By linking Gigantic Spright and Iblee into an I:P Masquerana, and making sure all of your monsters are in defense position, you are now able to lock down the opponents board. The opponent will 99.99% of the time will try to normal summon a monster in order to link it and Iblee away to unlock their board. When they do this, you just link IP and a ritual monster (most often will be Mitama as per normal Mitsurugi end boards) into Dyna Mondo to shuffle whatever monster they have. If they move to battle phase to attack Dyna Mondo and finally break the lock, simply activate Dyna Mondo to re-summon Mitama (or any other ritual) from the GY in defense position, ruining their chances of getting rid of Iblee and moving their turn to Main Phase 2, guarunteeing that you get to go to the next turn!

This build of deck is the next generation of Mitsurugi Ritual Hybrids. Feel free to improve this concept. Enjoy!

deck_description:
Thought I'd share my take on the deck.

Running all the DoomZ cards for consistency.

Medius and his associated spells because he's the best starter and getting to him is really strong.

Seventh Tachyon + Big Jaws lets you access basically the whole deck. Number 102 searches Medius, Number 101 searches Big Jaws and number 107 searches Drastea. You can really fill any holes in your opening hand by just searching whatever you're missing so I feel running the targets in extra is a small price to pay, especially when atleast 101 is useful for board breaking.

Because of Big Jaws + Shark Drake you also have access to XYZ that need 3 monsters as material. I chose the Dark Matter Demolition line because its the easiest to get going, but you could just as easily make Shark Drake LeVeiss if you're able to search an equip, which is slightly better to me because it OTKs easier, the monster negate works anywhere and it has good stats to stick around.

All in all I feel this strikes a good balance of consistency and power, although droll does hurt a bit if you don't have extension.

Virtual World has always been verstaile going first or second. Since the Full Armored cards are currently zero points, it is a powerful disruption tool and boardbreaker tools which generates draw power and discard fodder for the Virtual World Gates. Also, Snake-Eyes Vengenance Dragon is a powerful Level 12 Synchro that suits that deck well. You can negate an effect with Qinglong then use it for Vengenance to pop during the Battle Phase.

  • Going First - Make Shenshen, Full Armored Dark Knight Lancer and/or Snake-Eyes Vengenance Dragon with Chuche set up.
  • Going Second - Utopia Beyond + Stardust Charge Warrior is an OTK on unprepared boards. People don't know the second secret effect.
  • Boardbreaking: The Extra Deck is filled with options depending on the situation in addition to the in-engine Virtual World Gates.
  • Side - More going second tools and Gravity Collapse as an omni-negate going first. Use with Shenshen since it can revive itself.

The deck has a history of bricking and this version is no different. Preventing the first VW effect is crucial to stopping this deck. Not having Chuche access affects the grindgame considerably. The cost for Lulu is irritating and restricts you to 91 points, which does limit some good low cost point cards. The lack of the Extra Monster Zone hurts since we can't play Geomathmech Final Sigma in this format, which is brutal with Utopia Beyond.

Overall, Virtual World is still Virtual World.

Master the Ninja Arts of flips!
deck_description:
Control the battlefield by mastering battle positions! Flip your opponent’s monsters face-down defense to decide the fate of the duel!

Some Tips

Lord of the Heavenly Prison protects every set card on the field from card effect destruction. This means you can target your own face-down monster with Final Bringer of the End Times without risking their destruction. However, if you target one of your opponent's set cards, then it also wouldn't be destroyed.

Flame Swordsdance serves as a backup plan in case you don't draw your Ninjas. It can flip your opponent's monsters face-down and special summon your Flame Swordsman monsters. Its second effect can tribute 1 face-down monster you control to special summon the Ultimate Flame Swordsman, a powerful boss monster, from your extra deck during your opponent's battle phase.

Ninjitsu Art of Dancing Leaves can tribute 1 of your opponent's face-down monsters to special summon a Ninja from your deck, giving you both removal and board presence.

Karakuri Ninja mdl 339 "Sazank" is mostly used as another Ninja name with a different type. Its effects rarely come up, but it can target, then send 1 monster on the field to the graveyard when it's flipped face-up. Also, it can attack directly the turn it is flipped face-up.

Credits to @BaconForHire for the original decklist! I made some edits.

Initially added the Primite engine to give me an alternate combo route that wouldn't get hard shut down by Droll. The main problem with that is Primite and MWTM both heavily rely on the normal summon. Eldlich was a great addition to give more flexible routes while also not requiring the normal summon at all. With three main engines able to make plays, it's much easier now to bait out negates/inturuptions. I didn't expect it to turn out this way when first playing MWTM, but this deck is a great rank 4ish toolbox deck. It's pretty flexible there, allowing lvl 8 synchros and rank 6 XYZs as well.

Something to note with this deck is to be aware of the restrictions on some cards. Seventh Tachyon is an amazing searcher (uses giant hand to search both MWTM and Primite Dragon), but locks you into XYZs until the end of the turn. Lordly Lord allows us to choose between lvl 8 synchros and rank 4s but special summoned monsters cannot activate their effects until the next turn. So that really limits which synchros you can play. Some other decent options for synchros in this deck would be Cyber Slash Harpie Lady, Crimson Blader, and Chengying (lvl 10). Some other ideas for Seventh Tachyon are searching Nefarious Archfiend Eater of Nefariousness to get a free summon with MWTM on the field. And using Number 101: Silent Honor Ark to search Surfacing Big Jaws. Free special summon if you have used a spell card that turn, but it does lock into XYZs only for the rest of the turn. Also extra deck space is so tight, I couldn't justify dropping Castel for Silent Honor Ark.

All 3 engines have amazing recursion. With all three pretty much having infinite resources if they aren't dealt with by your opponent. When one falls short in a match, the other 1-2 can take charge. All Apophis traps are normal monsters, allowing Primite Drillbeam to be live quite a bit. Even with you using Angel Trumpeter potentially every turn for an extra deck monster. Eldlich doesn't really interact with the other engines, it just does it's own thing. But it's an amazing compliment to both of them.

Darker Ruler and Gameciel in the main for going second, with more in the side deck if needed. And hopefully draw into your outs with the Mulcharmy handtraps. This is by no means the final version of this deck, still messing around with the handtraps. This deck is really locked into some high cost cards with Primite Lordly Lode and Infinite Impermanence. You need cards that you can set for your main Treasures of the Kings Combo, so handtrap traps are best. Unfortunately, the restrictions on the Dominus traps are too much for this deck. Purge locks you out of the Dark and Fire Monsters in this deck. And Evolzar Lars is a staple in this deck, I make it pretty much every turn 1 I can.

Another amazing going second card is Defense of the Temple. Pretty much a mini Super Poly that allows us to go into Divine Scorpion Beast of Serket, an absolutely amazing board breaker. Banishing monsters on summon/when battling, gaining attack, and attacking twice every turn.

There are 6 "garnets" in this deck, but the way this deck works, it doesn't matter too much when you draw them. The only objectively bad one is Golden Lord with no field spell. Seventh Tachyon is very useful for returning garnets, then drawing them the very same turn.

Still planning on making changes to the main and side deck, but sort of at a loss at the moment. Let me know if you all think of something. Hope you enjoy playing this.

deck_excerpt: Unoptimized Umi Control Featuring Neo Daedalus
deck_description:
Your typical Umi Control strategy using the Mako Tsunami cards. Including Ocean Dragon Lord - Neo Daedalus was purely a nostalgic decision and should not be genuinely considered for running a more optimal version of Umi Control. This deck less about consistency and more about "sending a message".

The deck is very Normal Summon reliant and your strategy will live and die by your ability to get Umi on the field alongside Kairyu-Shin. Electric Jellyfish and Sea Stealth Attack are powerful additions to that board.

Included Abyss Shark + Surfacing Big Jaws package in order to facilitate Stealth Kragen as a back-up plan (not running Gozen Match as that's 100pts). Having both Stealth Kragen and Kairyu-Shin on the field at the same time will be counter-intuitive to your strategy and should be avoided.

Seventh Tachyon is one of your best searchers for your monster pieces.

Extra Deck is possibly the weakest on this list as I had no clue what to add or use (this deck barely uses the ED but still, it's something that can likely be improved).

deck_excerpt: just a fun deck for when i choose to hop into master duel for events like the latest dc for example. advice welcome!
deck_description:
ive long since stopped playing the tcg and am master duel only. My fav deck all time is orcust. I love how they look, play and their story. Plus its nice they were a top deck at one point. So ive always kept the orcust core in every deck ive played and always will. Ive mixed orcust with live twin, tearlament, and a heavier world legacy package. This is my latest one. Orcust mixed with snake eyes and dpe. I love dpe and how good he is and difficulty removing aside from called. I love the snake eyes cards even though theyre no longer a top deck and are nerfed because of how cool they are. PLus do i need to say anything about diabellstar? her effect but also her design. 

I'm not sure if I can because I was looking through and having trouble finding one card that doesnt do anything and doesnt work well or isnt just a good card by itself, but I'm wondering if there's any improvements i can make. There's cards like a second called, lightning storm, droplet, orcustrated einsatz for the orcust stuff, mulcharmy, the dominus spell, caliga claw crow which is a free special summon and good for links. PLus malicious instead of dasher but I'd still need to take a second card out. Already at 41 and don't wanna go anymore above it. Problem is I have no idea what to take out for any 1 of those cards I just listed. So if you have any advice on what I could take out for those that would still preserve the orcust, snake eyes and dpe engine, i'd be glad to hear! so comment if you do!

deck_excerpt: A Genesys Format Magikey deck, Flexible extra deck lineup.
deck_description: Here, we minimize the number of bad hands by minimizing the number of normal monsters in the deck. Worst case scenario you end up with 3 normal monsters and no starters. Possible, but you likely won't instantly die unless your opponent just has it. Ideally you combo into Magikey Fiend - Transfurlmine and set your Magikey Unlocking and hope for the best. If you have enough, you can combo into Number F0: Utopic Draco Future. This is where the flexibility of the extra deck comes in, Magikey Deity - Ashtartu is rather bad for a Rank 8 Xyz monster so your only truly necessary monsters are Daigusto Emeral Magikey Beast - Ansyalabolas Magikey Fiend - Transfurlmine. The rest of the extra deck is flexible if you want to go for generic 8 synchros, 4 xyz, or opt into the listed normal monster fusions. Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment is a niche slot-in that makes use of the dragons from the primite engine. Primite Fusion  also lets you recycle face-up banished or normal monsters in your GY to use as fuel for Magikey Maftea or Advanced Ritual Art.

deck_excerpt: "Slow and steady wins the race." - some loser
deck_description:
Runick Paleo!...sort of, I guess.

None of the Runick spells can summon Hugin to the non-existent EMZ, but deep draw and Metamorphosis will ensure Hugin is summoned with some level of efficiency, right before the game is over.

Wind-up Snail is a lynchpin of the deck, providing the much needed task of a normal summon that can make Toad/be used for his effects, has a semi-relevant effect herself, and doesn't miss timing when sent to the GY.  Plus, she's a cutie.

All in all, slow to start and to finish, but if it ever gets to spin its wheels in a format rife with Droll and Ogre, then watch out buddy!

This is my perfected version of Paleozoic - with a dracotail package of 5 cards, the soldier dragon + laundry package as well as 2 sol now that he can't be sent to the GY by Sprind

I don't think there is anything here that could be cut unless you want to switch out Dogmatika Punishment for the third Canadia and another trap I'm running at 2 like IDP, or a third Time Tearing potentially. I wanted 3 Mirage, but really needed the 3rd Karma Cannon and wouldnt play Rollback or Trap Holic at less than 3, and Zeus is essential too so this is how I found it worked best.  There are 2 draw traps in Balance of Judgment, which can be rotated out for Hope for Escape when going first to pair with Rollback. 

Trap Holic + Mirage of Nightmare is just a game winning swing honestly, draw 4, pop Mirage with Trap Holic, chain a paleo etc

The side deck is just a guesstimate really, I like Dogmatika Punishment in main with Ulti Slayer in side with various targets - I did have Vallon here too but as I'm trying the Waking the dragons I thought that this could work well with the big towers guy. You can also use waking the dragon into Opabinia to turn on your in hand Paleos you draw off Mirage which is nice. 

I've played paleo for a couple of years now and its always a fun deck. Just don't lose to time I guess. Dragon Gate helps with that to set up a big final OTK, and the Mosquito + Sol play can reverse OTK people in their battle phase if you save a paleo to summon in BP 

 

The only other card I wanted to try was the new DOOD cont trap that mills 10, but it seems a bit win more here and hard to actually find from the deck

deck_excerpt: Revamp of my old STK, stronger in this format.
deck_description:
Konami made the mistake of giving me 3 Dimension shifter again in an even weaker format. While I was rebuilding the deck for the format, I also saw some good cards to add I forgot last time. Anywho, this deck makes people laugh, so t's always fun to play.

The Primary goal is to get relay soul set on the field, and use it on your opponent's turn to summon a monster that can remove itself from your field. The secondary goal is to make your opponent's turn as short as possible so you can lose as fast as possible. 

 

Monsters that remove themself:

Lilith, lady of lament- Tributes itself to search relay soul. Obviously can also be used to search relay soul.

Arias the labrynth butler- If you open this, another monster that can remove itself, and relay soul/trap trick, you can do the STK turn 0. Otherwise, can send himself to the grave after being summoned to set another trap in your hand.

Dinowrestler pankratops- Tributes itself to destroy a card. Can also be used as a board breaker.

Ghost ogre and snow rabbit- Sends itself to the gy to destroy a card that activates it's effect. Can also be used as a hand trap.

Artifact Lancea- Tributes itself to prevent any cards from being banished this turn. Can also be used as a hand trap.

Rescue ace impulse- Tributes itself to summon rescue ace fire attacker, who can draw 2 cards then discard 1. Can also be used for consistency. Can also be used as a board breaker that negates the effects of the monster with the highest ATK.

 

Moving from monsters to consistency:

Pot of extravagance- Banish 6 cards from your extra deck, draw 2 cards. You play specifically these extra deck cards for decks like dogmatika that send your extra deck cards to the gy. Can also play fossil cards for this reason. Sanwitch is silly, so he deserves a spot.

Pot of duality- add 1 of the top 3 cards of your deck to your hand. You normally don't special summon on your turn, so the restriction doesn't really bother you. Also you only play 2 of each pot so you don't open 2-3 of the same pot in your hand often.

 

From consistency to pure hand traps:

Mulcharmy Fuwalos- Consistency piece. Can grab you so many hand traps that it just ends your opponent's turn.

Dimension shifter- Busted card that banishes any card sent tothe gy. Single handedly ends turns.

D.D. Crow- Banishes a card from the gy. It's free, and I had 2 empty slots in my deck. You don't want to play something like upstart goblin cause your second priority is to end your opponent's turn as fast as possible.

 

Side deck is boaard breakers if the particular deck you're facing just doesn't care about hand traps, and their end board can stop the STK.

 

Lastly is relay soul cards. It summons a monster from your hand, if that monster leaves the field, you lose the duel. Trap trick/Trap tracks are just copies 4-9 of relay soul.

 

That's the list, Enjoy!

deck_excerpt: „Snake-Eye / Fire King / Diabellstar – A láng, ami sosem alszik ki: keres, rombol, és újraszületik, míg az ellenfél elég a hamuban.”
deck_description:
🐍🔥 Snake-Eye / Fire King / Diabellstar – Pakli Leírás

Archetípus és motorok

Ez a pakli három nagy engine összeolvadásából áll:

  • Snake-Eye – az egyik legerősebb modern kereső/archetípus motor. Képes folyamatosan generálni előnyt (Poplar, Ash, Flamberge Dragon).

  • Fire King – régóta ismert archetype, amely a Fire King Island-re épít, önmagát elpusztítva hoz előnyt (pl. Barong + High Avatar Garunix).

  • Diabellstar the Black Witch + Sinful Spoils engine – nagyon konzisztens keresőmotor, ami mindig beindítja a Snake-Eye kombókat.

Pakli játékmenet

  1. Turn 1 setup

    • A cél: stabil boardot építeni, ami negációkkal és follow-uppal rendelkezik.

    • Snake-Eye Ash / Poplar keresések + Diabellstar + Sinful Spoils varázs/spell generálják a kezdő láncot.

    • A Flamberge Dragon és a Fire King engine segítségével többszörösen recycle-ölő és grindoló játékot építesz.

  2. Turn 2 / Going Second

    • Rengeteg board breaker lap (Raigeki, Lightning Storm, Harpie’s Feather Duster, Evenly Matched).

    • A pakli könnyen átvág ellenfél nagytábláin, majd OTK potentialt teremt Accesscode Talker vagy Snake-Eye Dragon line-okkal.

  3. Grind game előny

    • A Fire King engine folyamatosan újra jön a gy墓ből (Barong, Garunix), míg a Snake-Eye Flamberge visszahozza a board presence-t.

    • Ezért hosszabb duel-ekben is nagyon nehéz kimeríteni a paklit.

Erősségek

✅ Rendkívül konzisztens (sok kereső lap, mindig megtalálja a motorokat).
✅ Erős kombó + grind game – nem csak egy körös OTK, hanem hosszú játékban is tartható.
✅ Rugalmas: tud menni elsőként (kontroll tábla) vagy másodikként (board breaker + OTK).
✅ Sok meta tech kártyát (hand trap, Raigeki, Imperm) képes beépíteni helyveszteség nélkül.

Gyengeségek

 

❌ Nagyon érzékeny hand trap-ekre (pl. Ash Blossom, Droll & Lock Bird, Dimension Shifter).
❌ Ha a Field Spell-eket (Fire King Island / Snake-Eye field spell) azonnal kiütik, a pakli lassul.
❌ Első körben, ha nincs megfelelő nyitás, a védelme gyengébb lehet, mint klasszikus kontroll pakliké (pl. Labrynth).

deck_excerpt: ygoprodeck.com, yugipedia.com, yugioh.fandom.com, yugiohtopdecks.com, ygorganization.com, rushcard.io, discordapp.com/discord.gg, imgur.com,
Relatively standard LL deck inspired by Tom K's lists
deck_description:
Novelties explained:

Spell Card "Monster Reborn" - Super underated card in the deck. You can resummon Liger after a Lava G, Use it to play through HTs, Get a Leo for free on board and disrupt opponents, sensational card.

Sauravis - I always side out fuwa and HP going first so I need 6 going first cards in my side to ensure I can push through whatever my opponent sides in. I have 3 Ash for fuwa, aswell as another FBG and a TBGL which left me with 1 more card. You could drop Sauravis for a LS/FD and run FD as card 6 but with my siding tendancies I found I rarely wanted any more of those cards and thus I opted for a Sauravis for of use as it can be used on both mine and the opponent's turn. (Also has a funny but niche interaction with SCMR where you can use it on your turn, resummon it on your field, then on the opponents turn you have a SS negate + banish and after that protection.

I chose not to run impulse as I'm opting for a board breaker approach and imo one ss negate and the cost of turning of Ptol and Cross-Sheep probably is not worth it over another breaker. Would recommend running it in HT builds tho.

Get Golden Rule in hand + Carbuncle in hand/grave (Golden Rule; Normal Level 4 Crysal Beast, Synchro into Power Tool using Revoltion Synchron in hand and the level 4, reveal 3 Golden Rule off of Power Tool. Carbuncle; Add it off of Crystal Bond / Normal Sapphire Pegasus, place Crystal Beast Rainbow Dragon, CB Rainbow Dragon effect banish itself, special carbuncle from deck and add Rainbow Dragon. Link Sapphire Pegasus + Carbuncle into Cross-Sheep/Foolish Burial Goods send Rainbow Bridge of Salvation. Salvation effect, banish itself, add Carbuncle + Kyoutou Waterfront. Chicken Game if Kyoutou Waterfront Already in hand. Activate Chicken Game if in hand, draw 1. Else/after that, activate Kyoutou Waterfront/Rainbow Bridge of the Heart effect destroy Crystal Beast to add Crystal Bond, Bond add Carbuncle + Place tortise/cat). Activate Golden Rule, place 2 Sapphire Pegasus, special Carbuncle from hand. New chain Carbuncle effect, special both Sapphire Pegasai. New chain, 1 Sapphire Pegasus, 2 Sapphire Pegasus, place 2 Crystal Beasts in spell/trap. 

2. With 2 Sapphire Pegasus, Rank 4 XYZ into Gallant Granite. Gallant Granite add Morphing Jar (Fossil Dyna Pachycephalo if already normal summoned). Link 2 into Cross-Sheep using Gallant Granite + Carbuncle, if hadn't already. Special from Extra Deck Snake-Eye Doomed Dragon, using both Crystal Beasts in Spell/Trap, into Zone that Sheep points to. Sheep special Pegasus from grave. Pegasus place CB Rainbow Dragon, if hadn't already, else place tortise/cat. CB Rainbow Dragon Bring out a level 4 Crystal Beast if possible. Normal set Morphing Jar if possible, else Link 4 monsters using everything, for Saryuja, Saryuja special Pachycephalo. If normal set Morphing Jar, link 4 into Borrelguard Dragon using Cross-Sheep, Pegasus, + Doomed. Set any book of Taiyou/Eclipse. Use WAKE CUP! Mocha if possible to flip Morphing Jar. Else, Borrelguard flip Morphing Jar into face-up defense. Chain Book of Moon on Morphing Jar if possible. Discard hand and get a new one.

3. Continue Flipping up and down. As long as possible. Use Saryuja to bring out Gamaciel whenever possible. Pass hopefully on Gamaciel + S:P + Set Imperm.

Siding:

A. Side in Droll + Ash for going against Rouge Decks/Meta that struggles against Droll. If siding in both, side in Doomed for Overdragon. Side out 3 Imperm, + 3 of Amber Mamoth, Topaz Tiger, Cobalt Eagle, Amathyst Cat, or Emerald Tortise.
B. Side in Heat Wave + Non Aggression Area if you want to be cruel. Side out 3 Imperm, + 1 A/D Changer + 1 WAKE CUP! Mocha + 1 Book of Moon. 
C. Side in Morphing Jar/Card Destruction in need more hand rips. Side out Called By for 1 of those.

deck_excerpt: DoomZ; Genesys Format; Artmage; Going Second; XYZ
deck_description:
A Going Second version of DoomZ for Genesys Format.

The idea is born in order to use the deck's boardbreaking potential at its maximum, while also putting consistency to the max.

I trought about using Angelica's Angelic Ring, which you absolutely can, but to me it wasn't worth it for a going second version. If you do tho, you can take out Kumongous, the Sticky String Kaiju (Which I put for Lunalight, in case it becomes popular in the format), to put one ring and two copies of options between Gordian Slicer or Spell Card "Monster Reborn" . The rest of the side deck is for scenarios in which you're forced to go first.

The point of this version is to set up Jupiter the Power Patron of Destruction as fast as you can, trough both DoomZ XII End - Drastrius , which allows you to equip two of the opponent's monsters, one on summon, and one when you negate an effect on field, and trough the destruction of DoomZ Break - Diactorus , you can search the third equip spell necessary. Keep in mind that Jupiter, trough DoomZ Command "D.O.O.M.D.U.R.G." will be able to attack directly, for a total of 7500 attack points!

deck_excerpt: Turning your monsters into Continuous Spells one monster at a time!
deck_description: This deck is designed to break monster heavy boards. Poplar combos really well with Final Bringer of the End Times. You lead with the Snake-Eyes to chew through interaction and hopefully set a situation where you have two monsers in your S/T Zone to go into Doomed Dragon. As a supplementary engine, I use the Diabell cards to faciliate Vengenance Dragon following Diabell Vengenance's pop effect. The Sinful Spoils cards are selected to assist with pushing through plays and have some backrow if you go first. I opted against the Level 7 Diabellstar engine with Wanted as it was too expensive and did not quite do what I wanted. The side is filled with targeted hate for certain strageties and Breakthrough Skill combos with Foolish Burial Goods if needed. This deck struggles against backrow heavy decks and targeted banished effects on your Sinful Spoils engine. Can be bricky with multiple Oak, but am struggling to find appropriate replacements for it.

A P.U.N.K. deck focused on the recent Psychic cards rather than Gold Pride. E-tele is unfortunately 40pts but multiple cards can get to it, allowing more cards to lead to full combo through interaction.

deck_excerpt: But of course, it's Dream Mirror
deck_description:
Dream Mirror is not an interesting Deck. It is a tragic one. Like you can literally compare the absolute travesty that is Dream Mirror’s archetypal gimmick to the tragedy of Oedipus. The archetype debuted as a TCG exclusive archetype in RIRA in 2019 and got its second wave of TCG support also in 2019 in CHIM. I don’t know how you could play the Deck out of RIRA, and while it got more cards in CHIM, the Deck was still pretty much near unplayable due to its archetypal gimmick. After its BLVO support from the OCG in 2021, the Deck had better tools to work with, but because the other 75% of its cards were locked into their stupid gimmick, the Deck still was bad. After a single other piece of support in BACH in 2022 in the form of Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Traitor, the Deck finally had a good starter. Actually, it finally got A STARTER because you can’t convince me that activate Dream Mirror of Joy and Normal Summon Ikelos, the Dream Mirror Mara is a viable starting point for the Deck. Was the Deck playable after Neiroy? It was more playable, but still bad. However, it did trick some people into experimenting with Fiendsmith Dream Mirror since last year, because Dark Neiroy is a DARK Fiend who can change its Attribute to LIGHT. And now here we are: Post DUAD, going into DOOD. With the TCG exclusives of Buio, the Dawn’s Light, Mutiny in the Sky, and Luce the Dusk’s Dark, Dream Mirror is a little more playable, but not by that much. Dark Neiroy is still the Deck’s only starter, the Deck still is tied down by its dumb gimmick, and like 90% of the ways the Deck tutors its cards are nightmarishly bad.

Dream Mirror’s gimmick is that the Deck revolves around its 2 Field Spells: Dream Mirror of Joy and Dream Mirror of Terror. They actually don’t do much for the Deck other than allow your Dream Mirror monsters to access their effects. Other than for the 2 Neiroys, the DARK Dream Mirrors can Quick Effect Tribute themselves when Joy is in a Field Zone to Special Summon their LIGHT version from your Deck while the LIGHT Dream Mirrors can Quick Effect Tribute themselves when Terror is in a Field Zone to Special Summon their DARK version from your Deck. Save for the 2 Neiroys again, each Dream Mirror has an effect that triggers when they are Special Summoned by the effect of a Dream Mirror monster. But you need the Field Spells to even allow them to tag into each other to even access their trigger effects on Special Summon. And you can probably see where the Deck begins to falter. Without the right Field Spell and the right monster, the Deck produces so many dead hands, and most hands where you can do something usually result in going extremely minus for no real benefit. So what is the Deck’s goal? Before BLVO, the Deck aimed to end on Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Erlking with some number of Main Deck Dream Mirrors on field because the Main Deck Dream Mirrors Tribute themselves to tag out, which triggers Light Oneiros’s effect to target and destroy a card on the field. You also had some Traps you could end on, but mainly you’d be playing either Dream Mirror Hypnagogia or Dream Mirror Oneiromancy because I’d be damned if I have to play Dream Mirror Fantasy. After BLVO, the Deck got a new boss monster in Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Tormentor who was a Quick Effect monster negate while Terror was in a Field Zone and could also Quick Effect tag itself out into Light Oneiros if Joy was in a Field Zone. And then we get to BACH where we get the Deck’s first starter in Dark Neiroy. If anything, Normal Summon Dark Neiroy was a 1-card combo to get to Dark Oneiros. All you had to do left was draw the Traps.

In this Deck here, we are going to not play a Trap-heavy version of the Deck in exchange for some consistency cards and some pieces of non-engine. But, we have Mutiny in the Sky and Buio to give us more to end on. You want to open Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Traitor and a Level 3 extender. Dream Mirror Hypnagogia would also be nice, but whether or not we actually have it depends on how we open. Let’s say that our extender is Psychic Tracker. Normal Summon Dark Neiroy and activate its effect on Normal Summon to add Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Disciple from Deck to hand. If you were playing Fiendsmith, you’d be making Neiroy LIGHT by its own effect at this point, but because we aren’t, you don’t have to. Activate Light Neiroy in hand to Special Summon it because we control a Dream Mirror monster. At this point, Neiroy has a mandatory effect that activates when it is Special Summoned by a Dream Mirror monster’s effect which bounces a Spell/Trap your opponent controls. It still has to activate even if there aren’t any Spell/Traps on your opponent’s field. Activate Dark Neiroy’s other effect to Tribute Light Neiroy. This has you choose a Dream Mirror monster with a different Level than Light Neiroy from Deck and add either Dream Mirror Field Spell that is mentioned on it to hand and then you can Special Summon the monster you chose. Add Dream Mirror of Terror from Deck to hand and Special Summon Ikelos, the Dream Mirror Sprite from Deck in Defense. Light Ikelos triggers on Special Summon to add Dream Mirror of Chaos from Deck to hand. Activate Dream Mirror of Terror from hand and then activate Light Ikelos’s effect to Tribute herself and Special Summon Ikelos, the Dream Mirror Mara from Deck. Because you control a Level 3 monster, Special Summon Psychic Tracker from hand. Link Psychic Tracker and Dark Neiroy into Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss. Activate Cherubini’s effect, sending Buio the Dawn’s Light from Deck to GY as cost and targeting itself to pump itself up by 1000 ATK. Buio triggers off of being sent to GY to add Mutiny in the Sky from Deck to hand. Link Cherubini and Dark Ikelos into S:P Little Knight. Activate Dream Mirror of Chaos to Fusion Summon a Dream Mirror Fusion Monster. Because Terror is in a Field Zone, you can also banish materials from GY. Banish both Neiroys from GY to Fusion Summon Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Tormentor in your leftmost or rightmost MMZ. Next, activate Mutiny in the Sky to Fusion Summon Luce the Dusk’s Dark in your leftmost or rightmost MMZ by shuffling Cherubini and both Ikelos’s into the Deck. With this, you have a monster negate with Dark Oneiros, S:P to banish itself and another monster on field until the End Phase when your opponent activates a card or effect, and Luce protects the monsters in your rightmost and leftmost MMZ from being destroyed by your opponent’s card effects but it can also target and pop a card on field if another card you control is destroyed by card effect. This is probably the best that you can get out of a seemingly pure Dream Mirror Deck at this point in time. But, let’s say that you drew Dream Mirror Hypnagogia. In that case, you can Fusion Summon with Mutiny in the Sky for Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Erlking instead of Luce. The same applies if you hard-open Dream Mirror of Chaos which means that you can search Hypnagogia with Light Ikelos instead. Hypnagogia places a Dream Mirror of Joy and a Dream Mirror of Terror from your hand and/or Deck in either player’s Field Zone (one in each). Because of this, we can use Dark Oneiros’s effect when Joy is in a Field Zone to Quick Effect tribute himself to tag out for Light Oneiros from Extra Deck. This would trigger the Light Oneiros you already have on field in order to target and pop a card on field. Again, this is probably the best that you are going to be able to get with pure Dream Mirror in this day and age. 

For the Main Deck monsters: 3 Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Traitor. Dark Neiroy adds a Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Disciple from Deck to hand on Normal or Special Summon and then you can change Dark Neiroy’s Attribute to LIGHT. You can also Tribute 1 other Dream Mirror monster you control to choose a Dream Mirror monster with a different Level in your Deck and add either Dream Mirror of Joy or Dream Mirror of Terror, whichever is mentioned on the chosen monster, from your Deck to your hand and then Special Summon the chosen monster from Deck in Defense. Dark Neiroy, as I have said before, is a 1-card combo that gets you to either Dream Mirror Fusion Monster. Really good card for a bad Deck. The Attribute change is there because it is supposed to help out with getting the correct Attribute for your Dream Mirror Field Spell that is in play and for Fusion Summoning either Oneiros. 3 Neiroy, the Dream Mirror Disciple. Light Neiroy can activate in hand while there is a Dream Mirror monster on the field to Special Summon itself, and then you have the option of changing Light Neiroy to DARK Attribute. Then, if Light Neiroy is Special Summoned by the effect of a Dream Mirror monster, including its own effect, it has a mandatory effect that activates which bounces a Spell/Trap your opponent controls to their hand and then you can draw a card and shuffle a card in hand back into the Deck if Dream Mirror of Joy is on field. Light Neiroy’s second effect could come up, but you are mainly searching it off of Dark Neiroy and be able to immediately Summon it from hand to then Tribute for Dark Neiroy’s other effect. Why are we playing 3 of this card? Well, that is because Light Neiroy can actually act as a Level 3 extender if you already opened a copy of it in your starting hand. Dark Neiroy searches for another Light Neiroy and you can do the rest of your combo with the searched Light Neiroy, but as soon as Light Ikelos tags out into Dark Ikelos, Dark Ikelos can Special Summon Light Neiroy from hand as your Level 3 extender. 2 Ikelos, the Dream Mirror Sprite and 2 Ikelos, the Dream Mirror Mara. Light Ikelos adds a Dream Mirror card from Deck to hand except itself if Special Summoned by a Dream Mirror monster’s effect while Dark Ikelos can Special Summon a Dream Mirror from hand also if Special Summoned by a Dream Mirror monster’s effect. If Dream Mirror of Terror is in a Field Zone, Light Ikelos can Quick Effect to Tribute itself to Special Summon Dark Ikelos from Deck. And Dark Ikelos can also tag out for Light Ikelos from Deck in the same way if Dream Mirror of Joy is in a Field Zone. If anything, Light Ikelos is the better card as it is a searcher for the archetype (albeit a bad one), but Dark Ikelos is here for Light Ikelos to tag into to provide the Fusion Materials for Luce of either Oneiros. We aren’t playing any other Main Deck Dream Mirrors, and while you can make an argument for either Morpheus, the Dream Mirror Black Knight or Phantasos, the Dream Mirror Friend, their usage would only come up in very specific situations. But if I had to say, Dark Morpheus is the more acceptable card to consider playing. 3 Buio the Dawn’s Light who can target a Fiend Effect Monster you control to negate its effects and Special Summon Buio from hand. Also, if Buio is sent to GY, you can add Mutiny in the Sky from Deck to hand. Level 3 extender who can also search for a Fusion Spell, really nice. 1 Psychic Tracker and 1 Psychic Wheeleder as more Level 3 extenders. I did consider 3 Speedroid Terrortop and 1 Speedroid Taketomborg, and while they would provide more material for us to use, the difference in endboards is negligible. Finally, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, 3 Droll & Lock Bird, and 3 Effect Veiler. 

Spell/Traps: 3 Dream Mirror Phantasms which searches a Dream Mirror monster from Deck on activation and while Dream Mirror of Joy is in a Field Zone, your monsters gain 500 ATK/DEF and while Dream Mirror of Terror is in a Field Zone, your opponent’s monsters lose 500 ATK/DEF. 2 Dream Mirror of Terror and 1 Dream Mirror of Joy. Both can banish themselves during the End Phase to activate the opposite Field Spell from hand or Deck, but I will just tell you that this is really bad and never actually do this. Not only are we playing none of the Dream Mirror Traps that actually recur your banished Dream Mirror Field Spells, but Hypnagogia literally exists which means that you never actually need to banish the Field Spells for their opposite version. While you control a DARK Dream Mirror, Terror inflicts 300 damage to your opponent each time they Special Summon a monster(s). While you control a LIGHT Dream Mirror, Joy prevents your Dream Mirror monsters from being targeted by your opponent’s card effects or for attacks except for your Dream Mirror monster with the highest Level. These continuous effects literally do nothing gamebreaking, or anything really helpful for you. 2 Dream Mirror of Chaos which Fusion Summons a Dream Mirror Fusion Monster using materials you control. But, if Joy is in a Field Zone, you can also use materials from hand, and if Terror is in a Field Zone, you can also banish materials from GY. Being able to banish from GY is much more useful. 1 Mutiny in the Sky which Fusion Summons a Fiend or Fairy Fusion Monster by shuffling Fiend and/or Fairies from your GY into the Deck as material. Also, while it is in the GY, you can send a Fiend or Fairy from hand or your face-up field to GY to add it back to hand, which is nice for going into Luce for follow-up. 1 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Small World. I originally had 3 Infinite Impermanence here, but I decided to cut them for 3 Small World for the sake of consistency since Dark Neiroy IS our ONLY starter. 2 Dream Mirror Hypnagogia which chooses a Dream Mirror of Joy and a Dream Mirror of Terror from your hand and/or Deck and places 1 into your Field Zone and the other into your opponent’s Field Zone. BE VERY CAREFUL because this card is not Set Rotation. Your opponent can literally just activate their Field Spell over the Dream Mirror Field Spell you give them, so it would be best to activate Hypnagogia in response to your opponent’s Field Spell activation or after they already have a Field Spell up. 1 Dream Mirror Oneiromancy which is a Spell/Trap Card negate and destroy while Dream Mirror of Joy is in a Field Zone or it can negate an opponent’s Special Summon of a monster(s) and destroys them while Terror is in a Field Zone. The more I look at this card, the more I want to play Solemns instead. You can cut this card for the limited Solemn Judgment or Morpheus, the Dream Mirror Black Knight like I mentioned earlier. 

Extra Deck: 2 Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Erlking which requires 2 Dream Mirror monsters with different Attributes as Fusion Material. Light Oneiros is both LIGHT and DARK Attribute while face-up on the field, which is here in order to help enable whichever Dream Mirror Field Spell you have up. If another monster you control is Tributed, except during the damage step, you can Quick Effect target and destroy a card on field. And if it is destroyed by your opponent’s card, you can Special Summon a Dream Mirror monster from your GY except for itself. Light Oneiros is supposed to work alongside the tag-out effects of the Main Deck Dream Mirror monsters. Yes, you can still make that happen in this Deck, but it is more or less still not great. The best way we can trigger Light Oneiros’s pop effect is through Dark Oneiros’s own tag-out effect. We are playing 2 Oneiros, the Dream Mirror Tormentor which also requires 2 Dream Mirror monsters with different Attributes as Fusion Material and it is also both DARK and LIGHT Attribute while face-up on the field for the same reasons as Light Oneiros. If Dream Mirror of Terror is in a Field Zone, Dark Oneiros can Quick Effect negate an activated monster effect. If Dream Mirror of Joy is in a Field Zone, you can Quick Effect Tribute Dark Oneiros to Special Summon Light Oneiros from your Extra Deck. The idea behind Dark Oneiros tagging out into Light Oneiros is that once you’ve used Dark Oneiros’s monster negate, you can tag it out for LIGHT Oneiros who may or may not pop another card on field. But more importantly, once your opponent destroys Light Oneiros, it can Special Summon back Dark Oneiros from GY or any other Dream Mirror in GY (which would then trigger their on Special Summon effect). 1 Luce the Dusk’s Dark which requires 3 Fiend and/or Fairy monsters in your GY as material. While it is face-up on the field, your monsters in your rightmost and leftmost MMZ cannot be destroyed by card effects. It can target a card your opponent controls and then send a Field or Fairy from Deck to Gy to destroy that card and if another card(s) you control is destroyed by card effect, you can target and pop a card on field. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Varudras, the Final Bringer of the End Times, which you can technically make because both Oneiros’s are Level 10. 1 Downerd Magician. 1 Leviar the Sea Dragon. 1 Number 3: Cicada King. 1 Number 49: Fortune Tune. 1 Muckraker from the Underworld which can protect your monster(s) from being destroyed by battle or card effect by Tributing a Fiend instead, which can trigger Light Oneiros’s effect to pop a card. Also, you can target a Fiend in GY to discard a card and Special Summon that monster, but you are locked into Fiends for the rest of the turn. 1 Cherubini, Ebon Angel of the Burning Abyss. Finally, 1 S:P Little Knight and 1 I:P Masquerena. 

Side Deck: 3 Dinowrestler Pankratops, 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 2 Mulcharmy Purulia, 3 Dark Ruler No More, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: Move over Tenpai, because another competitive blind second deck has entered the Masterduel - Gem-Knights!
deck_description:
Move over Tenpai, because another competitive blind second deck has entered the Masterduel meta - Gem-Knights! These chivalrous knights in gemstone armour have received their new support, and now they can spam the field with several extremely high attack beatsticks and is backed by a omni-negate in the GY (Gem-Knight Hollowcore) to insulate their plays. Hollowcore renders the Gem-Knights immune to Nibiru, Ash Blossom, Ghost Ogre, Bystials and any other interruptions your opponent sends your way! Common turn-ending handtraps like Droll and Lancea hardly affect you as well! After smashing your opponent with 12 boardbreakers blinding second and limiting their plays with 5 "Maxx C" handtraps, Gem-Knights should be able to combo to an entire army! The OTKing assault force tends to be a 4000+ ATK piercing Gem-Knight Ruby, a double attacking and burning Gem-Knight Diamond, and several other Gem-Knight monsters!
 
There are several ways to build a Gem-Knight army, but here is the common 1-card combo:
 
Gem-Knight Nepyrim = 3200+ATK Master Diamond (double attack and burn damage) + 4300ATK Gem-Knight Ruby (deals piercing damage) + 2700ATK Lady Rose Diamond (destruction protection and targeted pop if opponent activates effect) + 1450ATK Phantom Quartz + 1550ATK Nepyrim + Hollowcore in GY (omni-negate to insulate combo)
 
  1. Normal summon Nepyrim and activate it's effect to search for Gem-Knight Dispersion from deck. 
  2. Activate Gem-Knight Dispersion to search for Gem-Armadillo.
  3. Activate Nepyrim's effect to normal summon Armadillo. 
  4. Activate Armadillo's effect to search for Gem-Knight Hollowcore. 
  5. Activate Hollowcore's effect to summon itself from hand by sending from deck Gem-Knight Fusion. 
  6. Link summon Gem-Knight Phantom Quartz using Nepyrim + Hollowcore. 
  7. Activate Phantom Quartz's on-summon effect to search for Gem-Knight Quartz. 
  8. Activate Quartz's effect in hand to set from deck Brilliant Fusion. 
  9. Activate Brilliant Fusion to fusion summon Gem-Knight Master Diamond Dispersion using Hollowcore, Nepyrim and Quartz from deck. 
  10. CL1 Nepyrim summon itself from GY sending 1 card from hand to GY (send Hollowcore) and CL2 Quartz adding Hollowcore from GY to hand. 
  11. Activate Diamond Dispersion's effect sending himself to the GY to summon from Extra Deck Gem-Knight Ruby, Gem-Knight Topaz and Gem-Knight Lady Rose Diamond. 
  12. Activate Gem-Knight Ruby's effect to tribute Gem-Knight Topaz, boosting his attack to 4300. 
  13. Activate Gem-Knight Phantom Quartz's effect to fusion summon Gem-Knight Master Diamond, shuffling back 3 Gem-Knights from GY as material (don't shuffle back Topaz or Hollowcore). 
  14. Activate Master Diamond's effect banishing Topaz in the GY to gain the card's effects (attack twice, and inflict burn equal to monster's attack when monster is destroyed by battle)
  15. Extend further with other cards if needed. Enter Battle Phase and swing for game! 
 
Obliterate meta threats like Maliss, Ryzeal and Branded and OTK your opponent in one fell swoop with Gem-Knights! 
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_description: An attempt to copy my deck from Master Duel into Genesys

deck_excerpt: Ainda em fase de planejamento, sujeito a mais testes práticos
deck_description: Deck casual em teste para o formato genesys

I love Mayakashi, as one may guess from my profile picture. I don't think it is a very good Deck though. I have spent tinkering with an Eldlich Mayakashi list ever since Delta of Invitation got revealed for the OCG, trying to make a Deck that feels good to use, and I still have not gotten there. The issue with Mayakashi as a Deck is that you have 2.5 playable Main Deck monsters in addition to almost all of its cards locking you into Mayakashi monsters from the Extra Deck. The Deck is just tragic, especially in the face of literally any piece of interruption.

Playing Mayakashi in Genesys is a whole other story. The biggest thing that Mayakashi loses out on from how Genesys Format works is not being able to use Link Monsters. And that is a big issue because most of your plays on your opponent's turn rely on you having cycled through your Mayakashi Link Monsters. Luckily, this doesn't outright kill the Deck. If anything, I feel like playing Mayakashi in Genesys Format is very similar to playing Mayakashi in a Master Duel Synchro Festival, which I have done many times when I still played that game. You are essentially aiming to Synchro climb through all of your Mayakashi Synchro Monsters and set a bunch of reborn Traps with the addition of some number of handtraps in your hand. The only difference is that the playing field between a Master Duel Synchro Fest and Genesys Format are two completely different worlds. The Genesys Points System does not save Mayakashi from Decks that have the ability to play a lot of non-engine. Sure, it is somewhat better here compared to Master Duel, but at the same time, you need to remember that your own ability to include handtraps and other non-engine is also limited by the Points System, not to mention that Mayakashi is still a Deck that loses to a small breeze.

I don't think playing Eldlich Mayakashi is the way to go for Genesys. Eldlich just isn't that good, especially since it doesn't have many proactive plays when you are starting your turn other than Eldlich the Golden Lord's effect in hand. We are still going to be playing the Golden Lord, but we are playing him because we are playing Delta of Invitation, not because we are playing an actual Eldlich Deck. Delta of Invitation is probably one of the best cards that Mayakashi could've ever gotten. This is because it can Special Summon a Level 5 Token if a Zombie monster is on field in addition to sending a Level 5 or higher Zombie from Deck to GY on activation. How is this relevant? When you activate Delta, you can send Alghoul Mazera from Deck to GY, which is a card that can banish itself from hand or GY to protect your Zombie monster(s) from bing destroyed by battle or card effect. But if it is banished from hand or GY, you can Special Summon it and then choose to reduce its Level by 1. It's free fodder to banish from GY to reborn your Mayakashi Synchro Monsters that can bring itself back as a large, Level 7 body. The Level 7 is important because it can then Synchro with Dakki, the Graceful Mayakashi to put another Yoko, the Graceful Mayakashi into rotation. But let's go back to Delta Summoning a Level 5 Token. Again, If you draw Dakki, you can Normal Summon her and then Special Summon said Level 5 Token to immediately go into Tengu, the Winged Mayakashi and start Synchro climbing from there. Tengu is your second best Mayakashi monster, and one that  you definitely want to put into rotation. From there, you will be climbing into Yoko and then Gashadokuro, the Skeletal Mayakashi who is just a beater if anything. This means that Hajun, the Winged Mayakashi is not our only way to Synchro Climb in the Deck as Dakki or Shiranui Solitaire for Dakki alongside Delta also gets you there. 

Golden Lord is just a good send off of Delta since he can bring himself back as a big beater that cannot be destroyed by card effects for some turns, and his in-hand effect is also nice, being able to send a card on field to GY. Yuki-Musume, the Ice Mayakashi is alright, but you really have to be careful about when you are Special Summoning her. If you want to go into your non-Mayakashi monsters in your Extra Deck, you need to have a way to get Yuki-Musume off the field first because she locks you into Mayakashi monsters from the Extra Deck. She is here because if you draw her and Dakki, it is very similar to drawing Dakki plus Delta except that you can Synchro Climb starting with Oboro-Guruma, the Wheeled Mayakashi first in addition to sending Mazera or Eldlich. Hajun is Hajun. For Traps, I am playing 2 Mayakashi Metamorphosis because we need a way to recur our Mayakashi monsters from GY, but more importantly from banishment. 3 Back to the Front which very simply just Special Summons a monster from your GY in Defense, which does trigger your Synchro Monsters' effects. 3 Ice Dragon's Prison because we can Trap Trick for it and it is just good removal in general. 2 Solemn Judgment which is here because it has a good point value that fits the remainder of the points I had left available for the Deck. 

Extra Deck, we are playing 1 Snake-Eyes Vengeance Dragon because you can make it on a following turn with Eldlich and Dakki and it is just a really good card. 1 Shiranui Sunsaga which returns any number of your Zombie Synchros in banishment or GY to the Extra Deck and pop the same number of your opponent's cards. Very good card that you can get to off of Mazera plus Dakki (if you did not reduce Mazera's Level by 1), but you need to make sure that you have game when you Summon him because you are basically getting rid of all of your GY set-up with his effect. 1 Gashadokuro because he is literally just a beater and the worst Mayakashi Synchro (yes, even worse than Oboro-Guruma). 3 Yoko because its the best Mayakashi Synchro as it can nontargeting pop a card on field after being Special Summoned from GY. 2 Tengu which is the second best Mayakashi Synchro, but its a nontargeting Spell/Trap pop instead. 2 Tsuchigumo and 2 Oboro-Guruma. They help with clearing Hajun and Yuki-Musume off the field in addition to helping you Synchro Climb.  3 Ultimate Slayer targets: Garura, Wings of Resonant Life, Golden Cloud Beast - Malong, and Mereologic Aggregator. 

Side Deck: 3 Kaijus because good. 3 Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit and the third copy of Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion. And then 3 Cosmic Cyclone, the 2 Ultimate Slayer, and 3 Dark Ruler No More. 

If you want to change some things around, I would recommend getting rid of the second Purulia and the Judgments to play a set of Infinite Impermanence and 2 Transaction Rollback alongside a third Golden Lord. Mayakashi is not a great Genesys Deck because you are basically playing the Deck at half power because no Link Monsters meaning not being able to play any of the 3 Yuki-Onnas. It's playable, but don't expect to go too far with it.

deck_excerpt: JD go crazy pls believe me
Those who have faith, will bask in the glory of Agua de fuego in The Golden Land.
deck_description:
Infernal Punisher was made just for me.

Grab bag type deck with 3 main engines. MWTM, Eldlich, and Horus.

There are roughly 19 starters that can really start to pop off with just that one card. So in a 60 card deck you have an 88% chance to draw at least one starter on turn 1, and a 91% to draw at least one if going second. This deck is very flexible and can mix and match routes depending on what you want to do/what you draw. Man with the Mark is an amazing engine for going first or second. It is incredibly consistent, allowing you to pop off with 1.5 cards (need something to set to get the search off) and go into full power boards. Everyone knows about the control/stun aspect of MWTM, but it can really thrive as a going second board breaking strat with Divine Scorpion Beast of Serket. Defense of the Temple is like a mini Super Poly. And on top of that, Fusion Serket banishes a face-up card on summon (or from the GY). So With one summon, you can potentially get rid of two monsters. Without targeting, or destroying. Then you get to attack twice with your beefed up dude.

This deck has the power to blow its load immediatly and spit everything out at once if it wants to, but that isn't the best method. The board can easily get clogged if you just go nuts with combos. Lots of trap monsters that kind of become useless after a certain point. Besides using them for extra deck plays, I have powerful cards like Forbidden Droplet (I'd run two if I had the points), Enemy Controller, and Infernal Punisher to clear my board and cripple my opponent or advance my board state with a lvl 6 tuner.

Aside from the main engines in this deck, it consists of board breakers, some minor handtraps (ghost belle is protection against opposing D.D. Crow), disruption, and some combo extenders. My Dinosaur engine is f*cking bonkers, I swear they made it just for me.

Extra deck space is crazy tight. A lot of good cards that I wanted cost around 10-20 points, so had to comprimise on a few. Star of the show for me currently is Snake-Eyes vengence dragon. Super consistent to get out turn one with your main MWTM combo and either a Ground Xeno or Infernal Punisher. Also can be made with the Eldlich trap monsters (as well as the field spell tokens) and the Blackwing tuner. Time Thief Redoer would be great with trap monsters as material, but I had to cut him to make room for others. Rank 4s aren't super common in this deck. But the Synchros, Rank 8s and 6s are made constantly. Jinzo is another stand out one in this deck, with its ability to tribute an opponent's monster to destroy another face-up card (as long as a trap is on the field).

 

Side deck isn't fully fleshed out yet. I don't have anything for specific matchups. Just some strong going first cards, as well as some more going second cards to add in certain matchups. 

Side note: I don't see anyone talking about Swords of Concealing Light. Very strong effect that HAS to be negated against most decks. The entire idea around building this deck was to bait out negates/interuptions. I got so sick of getting ashed/drolled on my MWTM combos when I was playing a pure version of that deck. Sitting with a single MWTM on field and no other plays to make made me feel miserable.

Thanks for reading if you made it this far. I'm just getting back into Yugioh with Genesys, so I'm not super familiar with every current meta deck. Still learning matchups, but this deck seems to have a good answer to a lot of opposing decks. Win rate has been pretty high. (Playing on YGO Omega)
This deck is what I think yugi muto would use today. I wanted to make it somewhat playable but also look like a yugi deck as well.
Going all in on R3NK toolboxing in hopes to not auto die to getting drolled.  Normaling Serziel and getting bopped still blows massively but hopefully called by that protect it.
Dragon Ruler! Spam Rank 7s as much as possible!

This is a purely casual deck for locals only. Is it good? Probably not. But it's a lot of fun though.

Diabell Vengeance is an insane boss monster. So I decided to play this turbo going 2nd version to pick boards apart with alarming ease. The Magician Souls is a fantastic card to bait interaction pre-emptively. If it resolves, you win the duel. The lower power level of Genesys means that your opponent ends of less disruption so you can chew through boards with good hands. A really fun play with this deck is to use Sinful Spoils of the White Forest to hard Fusion Summon Snake-Eyes Doomed Dragon using Snake-Eyes Diabellstar, which is searchable in this deck.

Just avoid Odion decks ... and Droll & Lock Bird ... and don't brick.

deck_excerpt: Rose Dragon, Black Rose, Radiant Typhoon, FTK
deck_description:
This is a 2 card FTK combo (Either Eldam or Swen or Chant, and Any of Roxrose/Redrose/Black Rose Garden). Only 21 points are needed to do the FTK as it only requires glow-up bulb from the pointed cards.

1) Special your Radiant Typhoon level 3 and search MST. Normal your rose dragon and get out Black Rose Garden. Your Rose dragons need to either search White Rose Dragon or Vengeful Witch.

2) Sync Rage Rose Witch, send Bramble Rose and Glow up Bulb. Special the glow up bulb and the level 4 you searched.

3) Sync Garden Rose Maiden, search Black Garden. Vengeful witch will trigger, special out Twilight Rose Black Knight, use its effect to special Glow Up bulb.

3.5) Activate Black Garden. Do not forget this.

4) Sync with the Garden Rose Maiden and the Glow Up Bulb into Mind Castlin. Activate Black Knight's effect to lower mind castlin's level by 1 (It is now a plant thanks to Black Rose Garden). 

5) Sync with the Garden Rose Maiden and the black knight to summon Beelze. Activate the effect of Mind Castlin to swap the Beelze with a rose token on your opponent's board.

6) You should have a way to get a level 3 tuner on the board, either through the bramble rose or garden rose in GY, or red rose leaving a roxrose on the board.

7) Sync with the token you took and the level 3 tuner to summon Garden Rose Flora. Flora effect to send Black Garden and special another rose token.

8) Sync Flora with the token to summon a second copy of Bramble Rose Dragon.

9) Destroy your own black rose garden through MST.

10) The mandatory effect of Black rose garden deals damage to your opponent. When your opponent takes damage, Beelze must activate to gain attack points. Bramble then Activates because your opponent activated an effect to deal 600 damage. Repeat til FTK!


You can play through a decent amount in this combo, as you can use some of the leftover pieces for additional ways to continue the combo if you get hand trapped. You cannot perform the FTK if you can't get glow up bulb in the gy and a special summon of black knight, but you can still build a strong board with a decent amount of interaction (Radiant typhoon cards, Genex Ally Zero, and destroying your opponent's board with bramble rose). The rose dragons are strong at playing through Droll & Lock bird, which is popular in Genesys right now.

tl;dr konami set mind castlin or beelze to 100 please.
