Some may wonder, "What the hell am I looking at?" and "What's the deal with these ratios?" My answer is that I don't really know. I am not the most experienced player, and I’m mostly posting this because I need some suggestions (especially for the ratios, what to cut from the deck, and the side and extra deck compositions). I will try to explain my thought process behind some of the wackier decisions.

 

1 - What is the general objective of this deck?

This is a Link-less EARTH Machine deck. It takes advantage of synergies between Infinitrack and Machina monsters, as well as other EARTH Machine monsters, to create a deck with good consistency and high OTK potential. Compared to the TCG, the lack of Link monsters hurts its combo potential, but thanks to the core of the deck costing zero points, we have room for strong support cards such as hand traps and board breakers.

The general plan is to play on turn one, generate a moderately resilient board, and then OTK on turn three. We are also well-equipped for going second, with a large number of hand traps and board breakers to try to win the game on turn two. In fact, based on a hypergeometric calculator, we have more than a 75% chance of opening at least one board breaker or hand trap in the initial hand (if we count Urgent Schedule as a board breaker, which I will soon explain how it works).

The deck is not very linear and some decisions, such as what to add with Machina Gearframe, send with Machina Unclaspare or search with Infinitrack River Stormer  depends on your hand  and the board state.

The side deck provides tools to deal with backrow-heavy decks as well as some consistency options. The idea is to replace certain going-second cards, such as Dark Hole , Ultimate Slayer , and Urgent Schedule , with consistency tools (like Upstart Goblin  and Infinitrack Harvester ) when going first. When going second, we remove some going-first cards (Machina Overdrive being the clearest example) and add more board breakers and hand traps, while tuning these choices to the matchup.

 

2 - Why 50 cards?

I first tried to design the deck with 40 cards. However, I faced two problems. First, I am not a great deck builder, so I feel really bad when trying to cut cards. Second, I felt that the deck became more bricky at 40 cards due to the large number of high-level monsters.

 

3 - Why infinitrack?

I like these cards for multiple reasons, but the main one is that a simple combo with an EARTH Machine Normal Summon and Infinitrack Brutal Dozer can search any EARTH Machine monster (just be careful, since it locks you into EARTH monsters), which you can then use to combo further. For example, going first, this combo results in a board with Infinitrack River Stormer  with Infinitrack Road Roller  as material (a poor man’s Bagooska) and Therion "King" Regulus  as a negate. Going second, you can use this combo to search a Level 10 monster and end the game with Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe.

 

4 - Then, why only one Infinitrack Harvester ?

I don't like to waste my Normal Summon on Harvester because I feel that Machina Gearframe  is a better starter (especially if you already have Brutal Dozer in hand), as it sets up your graveyard and can be used to search for follow-up. For that reason, I don’t want too many copies of Harvester, since we don’t need a hand full of Normal Summons. I prefer to keep three Heavy Forwards  instead, as they can search Brutal Dozer. I still keep one copy of Harvester, however, because in some hands where you don’t open a better starter, you can use Heavy Forward  to search Harvester as your Normal Summon.

 

5 - Any cool small synergies you would like to highlight?

- Urgent schedule = removal. 

While you can use Urgent Schedule  to summon a Level 4 and a Level 10 to easily set up an OTK combo with Heavy Armored Train Ironwolf  and Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe , sometimes you may be unable to follow through with this combo because of the opponent’s board or the lack of a Level 4 or 10 in hand. In those cases, you can instead summon Superheavy Samurai Trumpeter  and a Level 10 to make Centur-Ion Legatia , which destroys the strongest monsters of the opponent and lets you draw a card (while also being a 3500 ATK beater).

- Superheavy Samurai Trumpeter can be searched with Gear Gigant X 

At the end of the normal Machina Gearframe searching Machina Unclaspare combo, you can search Trumpeter instead of a starter for the next turn. This can be useful if you have a spare level 10 (Super Express Bullet Train or Heavy Freight Train Derricrane ) as it can summon itself and synchro summon Superheavy Samurai Brave Masurawo .

- Regulus + Gearframe

Therion "King" Regulus can equip Machina Gearframe  from the GY to summon itself. Then, Gearframe can summon itself with its second effect, which can be a nice extender.

- Foolish burial goods

My target for Foolish Burial Goods is Clockwork Night , which can be used to search any machine in our deck. 

 

6) Questions to improve the deck

As I stated in the beginning, I am not very experienced and want to try to improve the ratios in this decks. My main concerns are:

- What should I remove?

- Is there any card that I should change the ratio?

- What to do with Machina Fortress ? Since there are no link monsters, it is currently a 2.5k beater that helps setting the GY. I am looking for a way to incorporate it into the end board and maybe summon it several times per turn.

This started off as a generic Red-Eyes Metalmorph list and morphed into this over time. A few synergies that encouraged me to mix these engines:

1) The Metalmorph monsters need a Warrior/Fiend/Dragon, which matches the typing for 3 of the 5 Regenesis monsters, allowing you to make them either as a pivot off of something like DRNM after going first. Tributing the Regenesis monsters for a trap on your opponent's turn also sets them up to be returned to your hand via their own effects in the opponent's end phase.

2) Running Regenesis monsters for our main engine allows us not only to play with a pretty flexible engine, but also incorporate something like Dogmatika to break our opponent's boards or interrupt them when they're going first, as both Fleurdelis cards have 2500 ATK and DEF and can be used to bring out Archfiend or Lord. In addition, Lava Golem and Metalflame Swordsman both have a 2500 statline that can be used to bring out Archfiend.

3) The flexibility of this engine allows you to comfortably play second and go for board breakers in the form of cards like Ultimate Slayer, Gordian Slicer, and Lava Golem, make easy Rank 8 plays off of monsters from all 3 engines for cards like Garunix, Azure-Eyes, or Dingirsu, and when going first you can comfortably set up 3-5 forms of interaction with several coming from your own engine. The Dogmatika trap cards do lock you out of extra deck usage after using them, but you'll still have games where you won't be able to activate either of them and still need to be able to break a board.

Extra deck and side could probably use work and be tailored to your preference- Five Headed Dragon is just there for high ATK targets for Dogmatika Punishment.

All-in-all, a pretty fun deck so far from my playing of it! I think this format has the option to really let going second decks shine, and it's nice to play something that can do both comfortably!

If anyone has suggestions on things that would make it better, feel free to comment! :)

deck_excerpt: Break the board, summon big dudes, win the game.
deck_description:
Break the board, summon big dudes, win the game.

 

In default TCG you run 3x Statue and 3x Advance. Since we cannot do that, we run one each to at least search.

 

2x Frame to replace the Statues (it's a stater, I normally run 1 of them since you cannot summon Wyvern off of Statue).

 

2x the wierd UA field spell to replace Advance.

 

Since we have more stuff that stays on field in back row, we run more stuff to blow up our own cards. MST can aim for our own cards, so things like Clockwork Night + MST is a crappy starter if needed.

 

Heavy Storm is a must, since it doubles as a starter enabler if needed due to nature of the deck. Can also search off Triple Tactics Thrust.

 

We cannot run the link monster, so this is replaced with Synchros that can be summoned off of the targets for Urgent Schdule. This turns Urgent Schedule into almost a board breaker, since you have instant access to the dragon mech monsters. Additionally, Magical Hound can be used if it wasn't banished after hitting the grave.

 

I threw in Chengying becuase I could not think of another better generic lvl 10 and he is also funny. Note that he cannot attack under urgent schdule. If you wanted, you could go all in and summon Baronne with this, but the main deck Ancient Gear are limited so probably not.

 

Machina Metalcruncher is a lvl 10 Synchro enabler that is not a complete brick if you draw it. I might remove it since we can only run 3 statue anyway, and it needs the normal summon to use it's effect.

 

You can run the Kurikara monsters instead for possible disruption, since the tuners in Kurikara can also be used for Urgent Schedule and can be summoned from deck by the Synchros. I am not convinced this is the best way to do things, so side deck for now.

 

Rest of extra is Synchros for odd situations (hound + any level 4 is Samsara, then pass and pray I guess), or rank 4 toolbox stuff. I am surprised Tornado Dragon is not a pointed card.

The deck is not very good overall. It’s not wise to put all your eggs in one basket.

deck_name: Genesys - Block Dragon and friends (Adamancipator, Megalith)
deck_excerpt: Ever wanted a hand full of bricks? Ever wanted to Refill all the bricks in your hand?
deck_description:
* The adamancipator tuners let you dig for low level rocks. Supplier lets you add Guardian, Xenoguitar recycles from grave, Dragite draws, and carthoryn is a level 2 (make a 6 with analyzer for Raptite). Dragite is a strong synchro, as is Accel Stardust Dragon. Ruddy Rose sometimes just wins games but if you can help it don't banish your own block dragon with it.

* making a rank 4 gets you gallant granite, searches block dragon. All the small megaliths can be used for this, as well as most of your maindeck rocks

*only the search on block dragon is once per turn. This card is absolutely Diabolical. You can search all 3 adamancipator tuners with it at once, or Phul/Ophiel/Researcher

*Big megaliths are ritual spells in the hand. you need aratron, phaleg, or bethor to start most megalith plays. Aratron is a quick effect, bethor has the best on field effect when summoned (often by using Phul), phaleg is an extra name. If you want yoou can cut phaleg to play a second Bethor, this may be better tbh

*If no Big Megaliths are avaliable, Unformed [NOT ONCE PER TURN] can summon ophiel from deck by summoning 8 levels worth of monsters. It kinda stings to do but its fine because Hagith can search another spell 

*Ophiel searches hagith which searches unformed which tributes hagith for phul, which puts Phul (BEST CARD IN THE ARCHETYPE BTW) on field. Phul recycles a GY ritual into the hand, and copies its level [PERMANANTLY]. Phul can use itself or anything in hand to ritual summon any Megalith from hand or deck as a quick effect. Bethor is the best target for this, mass destruction on summon

*you normally do not want to tribute the Phul on field by its own effect during your turn

*Ending on Aratron kinda sucks because its negate isnt nearly as good as you want it to be, but it IS a quick effect ritual spell in hand during your opponents turn

*Notrah Plura is the boss monster you want. Its a solid negate and your only maindeck monster with exceptional attack.

*Anastasis is an absolutely diabolical spell. On activation , discard 1 to search a big and a small megalith and you're off to the races. When you ritual summon you can either draw 2/Discard 1, or TRIBUTE ONE OPPONENTS MONSTER. on your turn use the draw to get into all your adamancipators and during the opponents turn, use a High Level Phul to tribute itself for Notrah plura [or aratron or phaleg if you don't have the levels], then tribute an oppoments monster with Anastasis [NON TARGETING, NON DESTRUCTION]

*Notrah plura's hand effect is just okay. also its negate can sometimes tribute an opponents monster but don't count on it all the time

deck_description:
If you can't beat them join them.

A Weather Painter experiment.

This deck's goal is to win by devaluing the opponent's cards while summoning your own powerful zombie synchros. This event is like a modern-day Edison format, there's a healthy back and forth with a focus on resource management.

Some Tips

Conserve your resources. Don't spend your hand unless you're sure you'll win that turn or Lightning Vortex can turn things around.

I've summoned every monster in this extra deck and there are 4 slots left over for tech. I would include Evigishki Merrowgeist to take care of floaters if I had her.

Shiranui Spectralsword's graveyard effect can special summon Archfiend Zombie-Skull from your extra deck.

World Legacy Clash is a flexible card that allows you to dodge targeting effects, prevent otks, and trigger your Shiranui monsters' banish effects.

deck_description: Voiceless Mitsurugi go first & go second full consistancy

A fairly standard Madolche list using the Vernuslyphs and Ishizu cards as extenders. You can make this deck significantly cheaper by cutting the Seventh spells and playing 3 Pot of Extravagance plus any two other cards instead, at which point you just tweak the extra deck to be all three-ofs. A few important things to note: The Vernusylphs lock you into Earth monster EFFECTS, not Earth monsters, so you can use them to make generic rank 4's even if you can't use their effects right away, which makes Redoer and Tornado Dragon more viable. Also, not only are the Ishizu cards extenders and disruption, you can also use them to empty your own graveyard to make Petingcessoeur's special summon live, or to proc Chocolat-a-la-Mode, Glassouffle, Ticket, and Salon's effects.

deck_excerpt: My grandpa's Genesys deck has no pathetic cards...
deck_description:
Exodia Draw THRIVES in Genesys - access to 3x Into the Void AND Pot of Greed really helps this deck.

A hand with Summoner Monk, Toon Table of Contents, and any other spell you're happy to discard is ideal: TTC>TTC>TTC>Toon Bookmark>Blue-Eyes Toon Dragon is basically drawing 4 cards straight away. Then normal summon your Summoner Monk, and discard your spell to special summon Treasure Panda from your deck. You'll now have at least 5 spells in your GY to banish for Treasure Panda's effect, to summon a Flamvell Guard to Synchro off with Summoner Monk, summoning T.G. Hyper Librarian. You then still have at least 4 more spells to summon more Flamvells and Exodia limbs to make Formula Synchrons, drawing you another 4 cards form their effects and Librarian's. From here, just keep drawing and Synchro-ing as best you can, until you draw your Dark Factory of Mass Production(s) to get your Exodia pieces back in hand.

I also added some "Ultimate Slayer targets" for Extra-Foolish Burial in Garura (to draw), Blazing Bombardment Beast, Malong and Aggregator (interruptions), and Deep Sea Prima Donna (this is if you have inadvertently banished your Exodia head and need it back in your deck).

    1x Titaniklad the Ash Dragon
    1-2x Elder Entity N'tss

Took a crack at building R.B. with its wave 2 support and some silly little guys that I like better than more generic machine support or Machina cards. The main strength of this deck is its ability to cheat out Brute Blues with the easily searched Stage Landing spell card, OTK or just about OTK by resolving Pile Bunker, and its ability to survive via banishing Stage Landing and Last Stand. You can pitch either from the deck by resolving a summon of Lambda Blade, which you can accomplish by summoning Shepherd's Crook, setting Last Stand, and resolving it during your opponent's draw/standby phase. Lambda Blade itself provides a powerful form of play disruption, and you can increase your chances of resolving any card successfully by activating Next Phase. Also, read the main deck Appliancers, if you start with the field spell and one of the two Appliancer main deck monsters, you get three bodies on the field to start slamming your extra deck and resolving VALCan Booster. The ideal starting hand is probably something close to Appliancer field spell, Appliancer main deck monster, a special summon eff. R.B. main deck monster, Stage Landing, and Ash/Gogre. Also, Laundry Dragon is adorable and can be positioned for either banishing what it battles, or burning for the attack value of what it battles. Fun little guy.

The side deck I listed doesn't matter too much, just run what you think would be good based off of first principles. Probably don't run Dark Ruler No More though.

deck_excerpt: Simplify your opponent's gamestate with 24 handtraps then purify them with your phoenix flames!
deck_description:
Simplify your opponent's gamestate with 24 handtraps then purify them with your phoenix flames! While the pure Fire King may seem deceptively simple and therefore, weak - it is surprisingly potent in Masterduel's meta. Nearly every card triggers floating effects either from hand, deck or GY. Special summons can be played minimally in this deck to combat Maxx "C," or the deck can combo off with Promethean Princess to a Fire Link 4 fairly competently for a more powerful board. Fire Kings can also generate a ton of advantage and ATK power extremely quickly. The deck also has natural ways to combat the ever common backrow floodgates through Fire King Sky Burn. Fire King monsters on the field can also reliably dodge targeting effects because quick effect in-archetype cards like Sky Burn, Circle of Fire Kings and High Avatar Kirin all destroy your monsters.

Piloted correctly, Fire Kings basically has no "bad match-ups" in today's metagame, since it basically has answers to everything. Played "pure," Fire Kings might not have as much power as Maliss, Ryzeal or Mitsurugi, but it makes up for it with its versatility, adaptability and grindgame. All in all, Fire Kings played as a "pure" deck remains a solid meta choice for Masterduel ladder! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: "Pure" Empty Jar off a 2 card combo.
deck_description:
Combo Line:

1. Get Darkwurm in grave with either Dragon Shrine or Foolish. Have either Supreme King Gate Zero or Magician in hand. Activate Darkwurm in grave to reborn itself, then on summon adding whichever Supreme King Gate you don't have in hand. Scale Sumpreme King Gate Zero. Activate Supreme King Gate Magician to special itself by sending Beast-Eyes from extra deck to grave. Supreme King Gate Magician on summon add Lightwurm. Scale Lightwurm in other pendulum zone. Link-2 into Beyond the Pendulum. Beyond the Pendulum add Performapal Pendulum Sorcerer. Pendulum summon into Performapal Pendulum Sorcerer, Darkwurm, and Supreme King Gate Magician.

2. On special summon of Performapal Pendulum Sorcerer, destroy scales to add Monkeyboard and Skullcrobat. Scale Monkeyboard and add Odd-Eyes Synchron. Normal Skullcrobat and add Butler. Activate Butler to destroy Monkeyboard and special himself. Scale Odd-Eyes Synchron. Odd-Eyes Synchron effect to change Skullcrobat to a lvl 1 tuner. Synchro 6 into Blackwing - Boreastorm the Wicked Wind. Boreastorm send Zephyros. Zephyros reborn himself by bouncing back Odd-Eyes Synchron.

3. XYZ into Gallant Granite using Pendulum Sorcerer and Darkwurm to a zone that Beyond the Pendulum doesn't point to. Link-2 into Arms Mouser. Gallant Granite effect add Morphing Jar. Link-3 into Summon Sorceress using Beyond the Pendulum and Supreme King Gate Magician. Summon Sorceress give opponent Morphing Jar. Link-4 into Borrelguard. Arms Mouser effect when sent to grave to flip Morphing Jar down. Set any flip spells *other than Book of Moon. Activate Borrelguard to flip Morphing Jar up, chain book of moon to Morphing Jar's activation if possible. Keep cycling spells till you run out of gas, try to flip it down before you end. Then in draw phase you can activate Borrelguard flip it up again. Hopefully you discard your Jackopt 7s.

deck_excerpt: I'm trying to calculate how to make this deck master work.
deck_description: I'm trying to calculate how to make this deck master work.

This deck runs 17 + 3 (Thrust) one-card starters and ~20 breakers to hopefully throw more cards at your opponent than they have interactions to stop you. And if the engine makes it through, that's an OTK.

Brute Blues + Pilebunker alone = 7500 dmg, attached to a battle phase board wipe; add almost any random monster (preferably Cutter for the S/T negate and Brute Blues ATK bonus) and that's a quick OTK setup. I won't claim it's perfectly consistent, but in my experience a decent hand of breakers and engine is good enough to OTK through a Mitsu/Yummy endboard pretty often. And even if you fail to OTK, you still break the board and can pivot to a 2-3 interaction endboard that has a good chance of beating whatever cards your opponent has remaining.

FTKs are scary, but this deck has two ways to deal with that - either choose to go first and side in the 6 engine cards in the extra (first 6, swap Duster/Lightning Storm/Raigeki) for a ~5 interaction endboard, or side in Droll + Imperm to try to handtrap the FTK component (currently, imperm the XYZ) so you can still OTK through what's left.

----

The maindeck is cut down to 4 R.B. parts + Last Stand to minimize bricks, because you really need as much of your starting hand to be live as possible to break the really tough endboards. A 5th part (either Cannon or Rocket, depending on matchup) does increase the ceiling in exchange for reducing the odds of drawing enough live cards to break the board. I couldn't cut Last Stand because you do need some kinda trap as a backup plan if you don't successfully OTK, and you can sometimes make it a live negate by sending it off Droplet.

Also yeah, deck still dies to Droll, sadly.

King of the Skull Servants

deck_excerpt: Electromagnet deck for the Genesys format
deck_description:
I have not tested this deck in practice yet, but I was surprised at how cheap (in terms of Genesys points) it manages to be, since it has substitutes for Foolish Burial (Miracle Rupture) and Monster Reborn (Adamancipator Signs) that cost nothing. It is lacking in removal and general control, but I wishfully hope that Berserkion the Electromagna Warrior and/or Imperion Magnum the Superconductive Battlebot will come out and their effects will be enough to secure the win.

As for your game plan, your main goal is to ultimately assemble your Electromagnet Warriors in your hand / field / graveyard in order to summon Berserkion the Electromagna Warrior. He should be able to remove your opponent's stuff and beat them up.

IMPORTANT: Consider assembling your (level 3) Electromagnet Warriors into a Xyz Armor Torpedo and then activating his effect before summoning Berserkion. It's often a free monster and a free +1. You can also make some other XYZs from it if you want to.

Valkyrion the Magna Warrior is only there to be used as fusion material for Imperion Magnum the Superconductive Battlebot, which can prevent your opponent from playing. Don't expect to summon him. But, if you really need to, you can use Delta The Magnet Warrior's graveyard effect to do so.

I'm not happy with the Valkyrion situation, actually. The only thing we have for fusion summoning is a set of Polymerization, which you can only hope to draw naturally, since there's no fetch for it, and which is often a dead card. But Imperion is very strong, and can be summoned from creatures that are in your hand, so that's tremendous value. I don't know. I'm sticking with them for now.

I also considered more of a stall build with dogwood + ancient leaf with one day of peace, but I think reducing your lifepoints for draw power is more rewarding. Rochka may not be the best normal summon
Activate traps, maybe make an Xyz if you need to.

deck_excerpt: Fun, flexible combo deck for Genesys format!
deck_description: Uploading my White Forest list here for reference! In a format lighter on handtraps I'm maxing out on Astellar/Piri Reis Map because its such a strong starter even while requiring a S/T to send. I'm skipping out on Sinful Spoils/Azamina engine to give myself lots of points to spend on Chicken Game, because its a very fun card to use with the White Forest engine, as well as luxury handtraps like Ash Blossom and Droll, since this deck can draw into non-engine very easily over the course of a turn. I'm also running two Filia Diabell in the main deck to help if I lose coin toss, which I can side in or out as needed. This is a pretty modular list, you can change the handtraps to whatever you may want, or cut Chicken Game/2nd Fillia/Piri Reis Map for more non-engine!

Welcome to my build of Orcust! 

(Well, technically it's not my build exactly, but I'll get into that...) 

- 

Deck Summary:

As an obvious disclaimer, I am not a pro-player, much less a dedicated Orcust player on ladder, but I absolutely love this deck and am more than happy to add it to my 'frequent fliers' list. 

You're probably wondering why this build looks a little familiar. If you follow the tournament scene, this build is akin to Victor Torres who placed Top 32 at YCS Lima in September.

        (HIGHLY recommend checking out his list if you're interested in trying it out on paper: https://ygoprodeck.com/deck/orcust-650636) 

If anything, this is probably the closest to a 1-to-1 copy of his deck altogether, but there currently isn't an updated list for Master Duel Format (at least from what I saw up to this point) so I'll take the reigns and do my best to provide any insight on what the deck can accomplish. (EDIT: Refreshed the page only to find like 5 updated lists so please ignore this entire line, :)(:)


Yes, yes. I jumped on the Orcust bandwagon... It all started when I pulled a Royal Rare Girsu in a Legacy Pack in 2024 and tried to make it work with Jinzo, Knightmare, etc. Needless to say my efforts were next to futile, but managed to reach Plat before the recent support and found the gameplay loop for the deck to be quite enjoyable! 

This archetype first released in 2018 and has a bit of a cult following since then. The archetype itself shares a beautifully written lore that features archtypes like World Legacy, Knightmare, Crusadia, Mekk-Knights and even Krawlers! (spoilers: it's sad as f*ck) 

This deck focuses on DARK Machines and Banishing which is really comfortable given we're still in Maliss meta. Not to mention Mitsurugi just dropped, but I'm already going bald enough from stress so we're not gonna talk about that right now. 

Anywho, onto the combos!

Endboard & Combo Line Example:

The Banishment and Graveyard are going to be your best friends here. Any card that sends to grave for cost or resolution is going to work some magic for your Orcust pieces. The only difference now is that they're all One-Card Combos :DDDDD thanks to the addition of Galatea-I. Before, you'd have to pray they didn't have anything to counter Girsu dumping a piece to the grave on top of running some of the most resource-heavy cards just to fasciliate your plays. The deck was... not in a good spot before this support dropped, unfortunately... 

**That said, here's an example of what an ideal hand can accomplish: 

In Hand: [Dark World Dealings], [Orcust Harp Horror], [Orcust Knightmare], [Orcustrated Babel], Any non-engine/handtrap

*(This deck can play around a lot so I'm adding subpoints as alternative routes just in case)

1. Activate Dealings -> Send Harp Horror (be sure to check their graveyard for deck knowledge as it could be important) 
   
     - 1a. If Harp Horror gets Ash'd, you could always Normal Summon Girsu (if you have one in hand) and go from there, ideal dump on ETB would                    be Cymbal Skeleton.

2. Activate Harp Horror in grave. Special Summon Girsu. Resolve Girsu ETB effect dumping Cymbal Skeleton. Activate Girsu's second effect to create a Token on both sides of the field. From here, you can either use the Token, OR Girsu themselves in order to conduct the next summon. 
   

      - 2a. Ideally, using Girsu is recommended as, if all else fails, you can Link off the token for a [Linkuriboh] in order to soften the blow for a potential                Turn 3 comeback.

3. Special Summon Galatea-I (the art is so cuuuuuute!) Activate the effect -> send [Orcust Knightmare] for later then add [World Legacy - "World Crown"] to your hand (wait for it.) Follow this up with activating Cymbal Skeleton in grave to bring back our favorite sadboi: Girsu. (Sorry, spoilers...) 

4. Much like the storyline, we're going to Link off Galatea-I and Girsu in order to summon Galatea (the other one.) Activate Galatea's effect and return one of your Orcust pieces from the Banishment to set an [Orcust Crescendo] (love this card.) 

5. Remember sending [Orcust Knightmare]? We're gonna activate the effect in grave, targeting Galatea, in order to send [World Legacy - "World Wand"] to the grave. World Wand will trigger allowing a free summon of World Crown. Not only that, we can also banish World Wand, in order to Special Summon an Orcust monster from the Banishment.

6. By this point, you should have 4 bodies on board: Galatea, Orcust from Banishment, World Crown and a [Linkuriboh]. (Sweet Slifer, praying they don't have a Nibiru.) From here, Link off everything, except the Kuriboh, to summon our stylish new boss monster: [Enlilgirsu, the Orcust Mekk-Knight] (OH NO, HE'S HOT) 

7. FINALLY, Activate [Orchestrated Babel], set Crescendo alongside any counters you might've drawn from Dealings and pass. 

- Board Complete!!! - 

Follow-Ups & Tech 

The endboard might look a little light as this isn't the correct line to go, but there are SOOO many points of interaction outside of the endboard alone. Typically, it's recommended to play Orcust alongside another archetype that enables more options, but I prefer the pure build as it maintains a steady resource loop alongside my favorite thing in the world, recursion. 

With Babel on the field ALL of your Orcust monster effects are Quick-Plays including the Links in grave and on the field! Insane! I know! Meaning, Enlilgirsu's effects of adding a Banished Orcust or World Legacy card back to hand and sending it to the deck in order to steal adds a point of interruption. Mind you, it's stolen permanently so be sure to choose wisely. 

Alongside Handtraps and Staples, you have a ton in your arsenal in order to make your opponent's turn, really annoying. 

The example hand is merely a straight shot to Enlilgirsu, however I've managed to summon Dingirsu consistently even after being interrupted numerous times.

As far as card choice goes, elephant in the room, I know [Dark World Dealings] is a questionable pick as it kind of gives the opponent an advantage in either drawing a combo piece or some interruption, however... deck knowledge is huge and, much like 90% of the deck, it can bait an Ash. If it's not your cup of tea, feel free to add an additional Impulse and Imperm.

Sideboard: 

This sideboard is mostly centered around handtrap additions and potential alternative lines for extension. Really, you could go as far as adding a whole Synchro line focused [Borreload Savage Dragon] if you're really feeling saucy. 

I threw the Knightmares on there as I really wanna give those a shot, but the Extra Deck is already tight enough as it is so it probably won't happen anytime soon. Though, can't help but to hardstick myself in Plat playtesting these strats. 

Still, much like the story, you're able to slot in a good majority of World Legacy, World Chalice and Mekk-Knights as those archetypes surprisingly compliment Orcust to a certain degree. Almost like it was a marketing strategy planted by Konami... *Doakes meme* 

Conclusion: 

F*&k, I love this deck, man. Was so tempted to dismantle Orcust for other stuff, but these new additions have made me fall in love all over again. It sits in the Rogue catagory, as it still loses to a lot of points of interaction, sadly, but I definitely recommend playing around with it as it can be splashed with almost any DARK archetype. Though, most slottable archetypes that don't xeno-lock you would be just as fine as well. 

 

FOLLOW ME ON MASTER DUEL FOR ROGUE/MEME/NON-META NONSENSE 
181-209-956 


Also, feel free to use my campaign code in case you have a fresh account, or are just starting out: 00cdab64

A fairly standard Dinomorphia deck, mostly limited by how steep a price you pay for Rexterm. I can at least still run most of the traps i like to run. The only thing im still on the fence on is if N'tss is worth having over a singlur Trap Holic, but being able to pop a monster with Punisment, and another card by throwing N'tss away is just to much fun. I mostly prefer using evacuation Device instead of Get Out because I normally come into cases where i could have just used it over Get Out more common, but i do see it as the better option if you know youre going into a matchup that its strong against. And you can use Alert if your Rexterm gets poped to recur it, or you can go into a Laggia for extra safety against spells/traps, or even go into Rebellion for a way to go in for game instead. The only things id like to do if some points get changed around would be subsitute a Traptrick with Trap Holic instead, but other than that, add Daruma Cannon if it didnt also cost me points. Lilith is also a good option, but Wannabee! is just too cute! and you could honestly just swap D.D. Crow out for lilith if you are having consistancy issues, or just want to spam more traps. And you could use a copy or 2 of Reversion to use it as another one of your counter traps like Intact or Iron Thunder, but I didnt want to go over 40 cards, and seeing as how it only works after you use the counter traps first makes it a little clunky at times.

This is a deck I slightly modified from an MBT video where peepsYGO presents a Flame Swordsman Tenpai deck. I was extremely surprised at how... WELL... the two archetypes blend together especially with the Doomed and Vengance Dragon.

The video in question:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U4y94pjSNUk

To cut to the chase you're summoning vanilla Flame Swordsman attached with both the Flying and the Fighting Flame Dragon which can then lead to the Doomed Dragon. Alternatively you have your Tenpai stuff which does the usual Tenpai thing. Black Rose for board breaks, so on and so forth. Its simple but honestly really fun and if anyone has any ideas to take this further please let me know. I personally added Dark Flare to the deck however I assume the only reason peeps didn't have it in this video is cause its not in Master Duel for some odd reason. Either way that brings the total to 9 copies of Fighting Flame Swordsman which means that 9 chances to draw into your one card starter. Of course the Flame Swordsman stuff is the main part of this deck but having Tenpai in here really makes the deck a lot more fun in my opinion.

No EMZ? Well, Metamorphosis is only 10 points! Exta Deck is a very small Rank 2 suite and mostly made up of the Invoked package as well as a collection of Super Poly targets. Forget your Battle Phase, just turbo mill your opponent while putting up as much disruption as you can manage! Side Deck is full of the typical 0-point staples you'd expect to switch out of the Super Poly and/or the Invoked package(s) as necessary.

deck_excerpt: Albaz is truly the best fusion engine to play with Dracotail!
deck_description:
As promised, here is my 40-card handtrap heavy version of Branded Dracotail! The only "Branded" cards in this decklist comprise of only 4 cards, double Branded Fusion, 1 Albaz and 1 Cartesia. The 40-card variant of this strategy trades the inherent gas of the Branded cards for a an incredible amount of non-engine staples - 15! So with triple Faimena, this brings the handtrap count to 18 so you can bring your opponent's plays to a standstill where you can easily smash through their half-board. Post-side, the deck can take out 7 cards (all Dracotail traps and the entire Branded engine) to play up to 25 handtraps! Personally, I like the 60-card version of this deck better, I like playing with a high power ceiling and making gigantic Branded boards. 

Phryxul is the perfect card to bridge both Branded and Dracotail decks! Before Phryxul's release from DOOD, the Branded Dracotail player would be forced instead to go to Lubellion by sending Mululu and Albaz, which may search a Dracotail spell/trap, but neglects searching for a Branded spell/trap because of the lack of Albion. Forget Phryxul's effects for a second, her most important characteristic is her attribute - LIGHT! This allows Branded Fusion to fusion summon Albion using Phyxul and Albaz, allowing you to simultanously search a Dracotail spell/trap and a Branded spell/trap during the End Phase (aka Main Phase 3 for Branded players)!

As a result, Branded Dracotail is now a much more synergistic fusion of both archetypes! This strategy generates a ton of massive beatsticks on field, smashes through established boards with in-engine cards, and generates a ton of advantage! Albax and Phryxul has truly made the ultimate fusion strategy!

GLHF Duelists! 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

My Deck for Play Tournaments on Genesys Format

The idea behind this deck is to take advantage of the mutually beneficial effects of the two archetypes. I haven't tried it out yet, but I will be tweaking it based on how it plays. If I missed anything or you have any sugesstions feel free to leave them in the comments.

This is not the first time I’ve used /Assault Mode cards in Prediction Princess. Normal Summoning Psi-Reflector essentially gets you to a Level 9 Synchro Monster, and all that you really have to do left is activate World Legacy Monstrosity targeting said Level 9 Synchro. I don’t think that there has been any improvements in how /Assault Mode cards work with Prediction Princess other than their new cards coming out of BPRO massively increasing the consistency of the Deck and giving you incredible access to both their cards and their plays. But, greater consistency is always welcome, and so we are here back with another Prediction Princess Deck running /Assault Mode cards. 

Again, nothing has changed except for the Deck’s consistency. All you need for your combo is Psi-Reflector and either World Legacy Monstrosity or Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag. If we were to go with Kaku, we would also need to draw any Prediction Princess card. So, let’s say that we had Monstrosity. Normal Summon Psi-Reflector and activate its effect to search for Assault Beast. Activate Assault Beast in hand, discarding it to search for Assault Mode Activate from Deck. Activate Psi-Reflector’s other effect to reveal AMA in hand to target and Special Summon Assault Beast back from GY and then increase its Level by 4. Synchro Psi-Reflector and the now Level 8 Assault Beast into Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys who draws you a card on Synchro Summon. Activate Monstrosity targeting Crocodragon for Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Deus-X Krawler from Deck. Xyz Summon Mereologic Aggregator into the EMZ using Deus-X and Crocodragon. On Xyz Summon, Aggregator sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY, which triggers Herald in GY to search for Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Activate Aggregator’s other effect targeting Herald in GY, detaching 1, and attaching Herald from GY to it. Link Aggregator into Gravity Controller. Herald triggers from being sent to GY again to add Underworld Ritual of Prediction from Deck to hand. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotrei by tributing Bibliomuse. Bibliomuse triggers in GY off of being tributed and Special Summons herself back from GY face-down. Activate Tarotrei to flip Bibliomuse face-up and then activate Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect to search for Prediction Princess Tarotreith and another Underworld Ritual from Deck. Activate Underworld Ritual tributing Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down. During the End Phase, Tarotrei Special Summons Deus-X back from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon another Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and chain Tarotrei’s effect to flip Tarotreith face-up. On a new chain, Tarotreith’s Flip Effect Special Summons Turbo-Tainted Hotrod GT19 from Deck face-down. As a Quick Effect on another chain, Tarotreith can flip Bibliomuse, Deus-X, and Hotrod face-up. Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect searches for a Prediction Princess monster and a Ritual Spell from Deck and while it is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters cannot be targeted or destroyed by your opponent’s card effects. Deus-X negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s field and then Hotrod can Quick Effect target 1 other monster on either field during any Main Phase after it has been flipped face-up to Quick Synchro with that monster. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 2 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag which can Special Summon itself from hand if there is a monster in the EMZ. Also, you can target 1 face-up monster in the EMZ and equip that monster to Kaku, and if Kaku destroys a monster by battle, you can Special Summon a Monster Card that is equipped to it. I really like Kaku. Other than being basically a Level 9 you can freely Special Summon from hand, granted that there is a monster in the EMZ, it can also act as removal for a monster from the EMZ. And, it has a high ATK stat to run things over which allows it to Special Summon the monster it removed from the EMZ and equipped to itself. 1 Turbo-Tained Hotrod GT19. Its Flip Effect allows you to declare a Level from 1 to 9 and change Hotrod’s Level to the declared Level for the turn. Also, after it has been flipped face-up, during any Main Phase afterwards, it can Quick Effect target 1 other monster on either field to Quick Synchro using itself and that monster. Notably, this card is 1 effect per turn and only once that turn. As cool as Hotrod is, the 1 effect per turn and only once that turn clause absolutely ruins the card. You are so limited in what you are able to make with it because you cannot Level modulate and Quick Synchro in the same turn. I didn’t realize this in my Synchro Prediction Princess Deck and I apologize, but the card is still usable except that it is much worse than anticipated. And it is not like you can preemptively flip it face-up to modulate its Level to then Quick Synchro on another turn because the Level modulation is until the end of the turn. So, you are going to have to use it as a Level 3 Tuner. Yes, it can use a monster your opponent controls to Synchro Summon, but at the same time, you will be depending on your opponent Summoning a monster with a Level that you can actually target with Hotrod to Synchro Summon with. Imagine playing like Draco Berserker of the Tenyi because you expect to go up against a Deck with Level 5’s like K9 and then you sit down across from Maliss (you aren’t playing this Deck against either but just imagine) thinking that you should’ve also been playing Silvera, Wolf Tamer of the White Forest. So, if you don’t want to depend on your opponent, you are going to have to Synchro with your Level 9’s into Level 12 Synchro Monsters, which gives you access to Snake-Eyes Vengeance Dragon (which is a good card thankfully). I don’t want to harp on this card any longer. The moral of this story is that you should play a Level 12 Synchro for Hotrod to Synchro Summon with your Level 9 monsters or play Synchro Monsters whose Levels are equal to the Levels of the monsters that you are most likely to be seeing your opponent Summoning +3. 3 Crimson Blader/Assault Mode which can reveal itself in hand to add an Assault Mode Activate or a card that mentions it from Deck to hand and then shuffle Crimson Blader/AM into the Deck. Its on field effect doesn’t really matter as we are not going to be Summoning it Turn 1, but it prevents your opponent from activating the effects of Level 5 or higher monsters Special Summoned from the Extra Deck while it is on the field. Great consistency card for /Assault Mode, but also a nice monster for the Deck as well. 1 Assault Beast which you can discard to add AMA from Deck to hand. 3 Psi-Reflector which adds an AMA or a card that mentions it from Deck to hand on Normal or Special Summon. And you can also reveal an AMA in hand to target a monster in your GY that mentions it and Special Summon that monster and then you must increase its Level by up to 4. 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, and 3 Droll & Lock Bird. You can optionally play 1 Assault Lich which you can potentially search for follow-up as it can Special Summon a monster that mentions AMA or a Level 4 or lower Zombie monsters from your GY when it is Normal or Special Summoned. But, it can also be treated as a non-Tuner, so you can bring back Psi-Reflector for a Level 5 Synchro, Assault Beast for a Level 8 Synchro, or for another use which I will get to later when going through the Extra Deck.

For Spell/Traps: 3 Duel Evolution - Assault Zone. On activation, it adds a monster that mentions Assault Mode Activate from Deck or GY to hand except another copy of itself. /Assault Mode monsters cannot be destroyed by battle or your opponent’s card effects the turn they are Special Summoned. And, you can pay 2000 LP to allow you to activate AMA by tributing a Synchro Monster in your Extra Deck once this turn. Look at this Catalyst Field of a card. It does so much for /Assault Mode. For this Deck, this card usually just searches for Psi-Reflector. However, if you set AMA before you end your turn going first, you can pay 2000 LP on your following turn to activate AMA, tributing Crimson Blader from Extra Deck for Crimson Blade/Assault Mode for extra Link Material or for a big beater that cannot be destroyed by battle or card effects this turn. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. 3 Infinite Impermanence and 1 Assault Mode Activate. And as you may already know, AMA tributes a Synchro Monster to Special Summon an /Assault Mode monster from Deck whose name includes the Tributed monster’s name. This card is a hard brick in the Deck, so just keep that in mind. 

Extra Deck: 1 Elder Entity N’tss which targets and destroys a card on field if it is sent to the GY. 1 Snake-Eyes Vengeance Dragon which is our Level 12 Synchro Monster for Hotrod to make with one of our Level 9 monsters. It can Quick Effect target a face-up monster on the field or in either GY during the Main Phase and place it face-up in its owner’s Spell/Trap Zone. And then during the Battle Phase, you can Quick Effect target 1 monster and 1 Continuous Spell on the field and destroy them. Vengeance Dragon is the best Level 12 Synchro Monster you can access off of Hotrod and it is arguably the best Synchro Monster to access off of Hotrod period. I do plan to make a guide to the Synchro Monster options for Hotrod similar to what I did for Summoner of Illusions, so keep that in mind I guess. 1 Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys which draws you cards when it is Synchro Summoned equal to the number of non-Tuners used for its Synchro Summon. Also, you can Quick Effect discard 2 cards to target and destroy a card on field. Considering that you are making this as part of your set-up combo, if you have some way to put it back into the Extra Deck, it is technically a good Synchro Monster to Synchro Summon with Hotrod if your opponent has any Level 6 monsters. 1 Night Wing Priestess. If Special Summoned, you can set an Assault Mode Activate from hand, Deck, or GY and it can be activated this turn, but you can also discard a card to add to hand or Special Summon a monster that mentions AMA from Deck. However, this effect does lock you into Synchro Monsters from the Extra Deck for the rest of the turn. Let’s say that you did not draw Monstrosity or Kaku, but you do have Psi-Reflector (which is most of the time considering how many cards search it). When you bring back Assault Beast by revealing AMA in hand, you can increase its Level by 3 to make it a 7 instead of an 8 so that you can go into Night Wing Priestess. Priestess can then set AMA and have it immediately activatable, but you would want to have Assault Zone on field as well so that you can pay 2000 LP to tribute Crimson Blader from Extra Deck with AMA for Crimson Blader/AM. And then, you can discard a card to Summon Psi-Refector to Synchro with it into Crocodragon for a piece of interaction. Or, if  you are playing Assault Lich, you can grab that from the Deck to Synchro with Night Wing Priestess into Vengeance Dragon. So, without access to your Prediction Princess combo, this is still better than nothing. 1 Crimson Blader for what I just explained and what I explained much earlier. 1 Shooting Riser Dragon which we can make off of Hotrod targeting a Level 4 monster on the field. Level 4’s are pretty common, and Shooting Riser is a good Summon off of it. On Synchro Summon, it can send a monster with a lower Level than it from Deck to GY to reduce its Level by that monster’s Level. And while you cannot activate effects of monsters with the same name as the monster you sent to GY, you can still Quick Synchro during your opponent’s Main Phase. Imagine you Hotrod targeting your opponent’s Level 4 to Synchro Summon Shooting Riser. Now, you can Shooting Riser to dump Fuwalos to make it a 3 and then you can still Quick Synchro into Vengeance Dragon with one of your Level 9’s. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand when it is sent to GY. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 Dyna Mondo. 1 Gravity Controller. 

Side Deck: The 3rd Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag, 3 Dinowrestler Pankratops (I am currently in my Pankratops phase because I found the 6 copies of it I had since TOSS Format), 3 Mulcharmy Purulia, 3 Lightning Storm, 1 Called by the Grave, 1 Triple Tactics Talent, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: Medius is a very cool card
deck_description:
Contrary to the folk using Medius the Pure and Elvennotes Power Patron to make Armades, Keeper of Boundaries for Fiendsmith combo, we are using them to make another Level 5 Synchro here, Ib the World Chalice Justiciar which is going to search us World Legacy Monstrosity for our Prediction Princess plays. But Medius can do even more for us. If you Normal Summon him, you can use his effect in GY to shuffle a monster from your hand or face-up field into the Deck for a Level 4 on field, which you can Synchro with Ib to make a Level 9 Synchro Monster to then target with Monstrosity. Medius and Elvennotes Power Patron are looking real good for Prediction Princess, even more so than the Dinosaur and Draconnet package that I’ve previously played in Runick Prediction Princess, primarily because Normal Summoning Medius gets you both Monstrosity and a Level 9 Synchro Monster. 

While Medius by himself is basically full Prediction Princess combo, I am going to include another monster in the combo, literally any other monster in hand is fine. Yes, Normal Summoning Medius does everything you need, but we will likely have at least another monster in our hand which will allow us to enable a few more plays. Normal Summon Medius the Innocent and activate his effect on Normal Summon to Special Summon Elvennotes Power Patron from Deck. Synchro Medius and the Power Patron into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. Chain Link 1 Ib and Chain Link 2 Power Patron in GY. Elvennotes Power Patron adds Elvennotes Lucina from Deck to hand because it was sent to GY as Synchro Material. Ib searches for World Legacy Monstrosity from Deck because she was Synchro Summoned. Activate Medius in GY to shuffle any other monster from your hand into the Deck to Special Summon him back from the GY. Synchro Medius and Ib into Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys (to anywhere but your center MMZ) which draws you a card on Synchro Summon. Activate Monstrosity targeting Archethys to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Enneacraft - Astay.PIXIEA from Deck to anywhere but your center MMZ. Xyz PIXIEA and Crocodragon into Mereologic Aggregator which sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon. This triggers Herald in GY to search for Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Activate Aggregator’s other effect targeting Herald in GY, detaching 1, and attaching Herald from GY to it. Special Summon Lucina from hand to your center MMZ and activate her effect to search for another Elvennotes Power Patron from Deck. Link Lucina and Aggregator into I:P Masquerena. Herald triggers from being sent to GY again to add Underworld Ritual of Prediction from Deck to hand. Activate Underworld Ritual to Ritual Summon Tarotrei by tributing Bibliomuse. Bibliomuse triggers in GY off of being tributed and Special Summons herself back from GY face-down. Activate Tarotrei to flip Bibliomuse face-up and then activate Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect to search for Prediction Princess Tarotreith and another Underworld Ritual from Deck. Activate Underworld Ritual tributing Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down. During the End Phase, Tarotrei Special Summons PIXIEA from GY face-down. During your opponent’s Standby Phase, banish Underworld Ritual from GY to Special Summon another Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and chain Tarotrei’s effect to flip Tarotreith face-up. On a new chain, Tarotreith’s Flip Effect Special Summons Deus-X Krawler from Deck face-down. On another new chain, Tarotreith can use her Quick Effect to flip Bibliomuse, Deus-X, and PIXIEA face-up. I:P can go into either S:P Little Knight or Dyna Mondo. Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect searches for another Prediction Princess monster and a Ritual Spell and it protects your Ritual Monsters from targeting and destruction by your opponent’s effects while it is face-up on the field. Deus-X negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it’s flipped face-up. And PIXIEA prevents your opponent from targeting cards on either field or in either GY with card effects after it has been flipped face-up. You also have the Elvennotes Power Patron in hand which you can Normal Summon next turn to Synchro with one of your LIGHT or DARK Level 9’s to make Chaos Angel. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Enneacraft - Astay.PIXIEA which can, when your opponent activates a card or effect that targets a card(s) you control, flip itself face-up as part of this effect’s activation in order to negate that effect and then allow you to banish a random card out of your opponent’s hand face-down. Also, after it has been flipped face-up, your opponent cannot target cards on either field or in either GY with card effects. 1 Elvennotes Lucina. All of the Elvennotes monsters can Special Summon themselves from your hand to your center MMZ for free. Lucina is just the one that searches for another Elvennotes monster. Can’t really make use of her effect on your opponent’s turn because we aren’t playing the Elvennotes cards that help you reposition. I guess the next best Elvennotes monster to play would be Elvennotes Dyina which can also Special Summon herself from hand to the center MMZ for free, but she places an Elvennotes Continuous Spell face-up on your field. This can get you Elvennotes ~Homecoming Parallelism~ which prevents your monster in the center MMZ from being destroyed by card effects, so you can like keep that in mind to Special Summon like PIXIEA to the center to make it both immune to targeting and destruction by card effects. Also, it can send a monster from hand or face-up field to GY to Special Summon an Elvennotes monster with a different original Attribute from Deck. And while this does Synchro lock you, on your following turn, you can do your Link Summoning and Xyz plays before committing to Homecoming’s effect to get Elvennotes Power Patron from Deck who, again, can Synchro with one of your LIGHT or DARK Level 9’s to make Chaos Angel. Dyina also works as a Small World bridge from Ash Blossom to Medius I guess. 3 Medius the Pure. On Normal or Special Summon, he can add to hand or Special Summon a Power Patron from Deck and if he is in your GY, you can shuffle a monster from your hand or face-up field into the Deck to Special Summon him from GY but banish him when he leaves the field. There are so many ways to access Medius. You have Artmage Vandalism -Assault-, you can send him from Deck to GY off of Diviner of the Herald or even Armageddon Knight and then reborn him by his own effect, and the same goes for Theorealize. But because we are intending to Special Summon him back by his own effect as part of our combo, it would be best to play cards that add him to hand and not send him to GY. But, in a Runick Deck playing Medius, we can absolutely play Diviner and Theorealize to do just that. 2 Elvennotes Power Patron. It’s a Level 1 Tuner monster who prevents you from Summoning from Extra Deck except for Synchro Monsters while you control it, but the only one of its effects that we are actually using is the one that adds an Elvennotes card from Deck to hand when it is sent to GY as Synchro Material. As in the combo described, this searches Lucina who can then Summon herself for free. You can also search for another copy of Elvennotes Power Patron because why not. 3 Mulcharmy Fuwalos, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, 3 Droll & Lock Bird, and 2 Effect Veiler. 

Spell/Traps: 3 Artmage Vandalism -Assault- which just searches Medius from Deck on activation.1 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. 2 Small World. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 1 Called by the Grave. 3 Infinite Impermanence. 1 World Legacy Pawns as another search off of Ib in case we already drew Monstrosity. It can target a face-down monster you control and change it to face-up Attack or Defense Position. You can use this to flip up Tarotreith instead of Tarotrei’s effect, so you can save Tarotrei’s effect to Quick Effect change a monster your opponent controls to face-down Defense Position. 

1 Elder Entity N’tss which targets and destroys a card on field if it is sent to the GY. 1 Chaos Angel. You can play any other Level 10 Synchro of your choice as follow-up like Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying or Fabled Levilazebul. 1 Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys which draws you cards when it is Synchro Summoned equal to the number of non-Tuners used for its Synchro Summon. Also, you can Quick Effect discard 2 cards to target and destroy a card on field. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar who adds a World Legacy card from Deck to hand on Synchro Summon. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand when it is sent to GY. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Knightmare Unicorn. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Dyna Mondo.

Side Deck: 3 Dinowrestler Pankratops, 3 Mulcharmy Purulia, 2 Forbidden Droplet, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, 3 Evenly Matched, 2 Solemn Strike, and 1 Solemn Judgment.

This "Fire King" Deck is heavily destruction-based. Strengthen your field through cards whose effects destroy monsters and cards whose effects can be activated when monsters are destroyed. If you destroy a "Fire King" monster with the effect of "Fire King Island", you can add "Sacred Fire King Garunix" to your hand and then Special Summon it with its own effect.

This Deck augments the "Atlantean" forces with WATER Synchro/Xyz/Link Monsters whose effects build up your field and disrupt the opponent. Choose between various ways to disrupt the opponent depending on the situation.
For instance, you can banish your opponent's cards with the effects of "Trishula, Dragon of the Ice Barrier" and "Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign Chengying", or negate the activation of their Spell Cards and destroy them with "Adamancipator Risen - Dragite".

This Deck incorporates "Fire King" monsters alongside FIRE Link Monsters.
The synergy between "Promethean Princess, Bestower of Flames" and "Fire King" is especially good, since it Special Summons itself from the Graveyard by destroying 1 FIRE monster you control and 1 monster your opponent controls.

This Deck combines "Fire King" and "Snake-Eye". You can Set "Original Sinful Spoils - Snake-Eye" with the effect of "Diabellstar the Black Witch", enabling you to Special Summon "Snake-Eye" monsters or even "Legendary Fire King Ponix". Call forth "Fire King" monsters when the time is right.

This "Atlantean" Deck excels at disruption and removal. Give your opponent nowhere to run by combining the likes of "Mermail Abyssgaios", which prevents Level 5 or higher monsters from attacking, and "Number 4: Stealth Kragen", which makes all face-up monsters on the field become WATER.

deck_excerpt: It was just Sweant to be.
deck_description:
Realised that Swen enables a pretty good combo for the Goblin Biker deck.

 

Swen Combo

 

Special Swen, add Chant, use Chant to add Eldam, special Eldam and add Krosea.

Special BIG GABONGA using Swen and Eldam on field, add Dugg Charger, special Dugg Charger, add Breakout.

Tribute Dugg Charger with Breakout, special Gone Wild from deck and special Krosea with her effect from hand.

!!!DO NOT USE KROSEA SEARCH EFFECT, AS IT LOCKS YOU INTO WIND!!!

Gone Wild effect special Clatter Sploder from deck, Clatter Sploder special Dugg Charger from grave.

Special Evolzar Lars, Goblin's Crazy Beast or Gone Bonkers using Gone Wild and Krosea on field.

Use Dugg Charger and Clatter Sploder to special Exagard and detach Clatter Sploder to add Meltdown or Critical, or special Torpedo to draw one and overlay into Fortress to search Full-Armored Xyz.

 

All that without a normal summon.

 

Also the Radiant Typhoon cards makes it easier to summon Totem Bird, as it requires you use two wind monsters.

 

I love Goblin Bikers and it was fun to try this out.

deck_excerpt: Vampire, Shiranui, Mayakashi, Despian, Branded, Tearlament, Vandread, Bystial, Zombie World
deck_description:
This is my 1st uploaded deck. 

This is a themed deck list inspired off one of my favorite game franchises, Castlevania. I wanted to build something fun in putting together this deck list. I like to play with 50 cards decks to the deck and matches interesting. Tried to stay with the gothic, vampirc, monster theme as much as possible while considering what would be believable monsters/creatures/minions that would be in Draculas castle. 

I play with most of these cards in Master Duel and wanted to share it with anyone else who may enjoy this as well. 


I added Assault Lich as I've been playing with it the past couple days on 3rd party sim, and it's a good combo extender and recurrsion tool. I think it will a great addition to any zombie deck once it comes to the TCG. 

I hope the rest of these cards eventually come to Master Duel (Vulcarrion, Dark Necromancer, Moissa, Lich, Juraishin) but Konami always like to take their sweet time.

Small amounts of Copium sprinkled here and there, but y'know. All HERO decks are Copium anyway, I just did it in a way that's actually fun for me to pilot.

deck_description: Hhhm hhm yes cheap indeed .can save some bucks from only using one fraktall .He's extremely easily accessible via Mouser and some Tri-brigade spells.
"Wow, an archetype inspired by Dark Souls?  I can't wait to see how cool they are!"

Dracotail + Branded

Side Deck Patterns

VS Yummy Going 2°

Entra: Fantastical Dragon Phantazmay x3, Dinowrestler Pankratops  x1

Sale: Effect Veiler x2, Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit  x2

  • Phantazmay al Yummy★Snatchy en turno rival para robar 2 y forzar ash u otra, se puede negar y destruir el efecto de los synchros.
  • Pankratops al iniciar mi Main Phase 1, no inicia cadena, pasar al ataque, intentar atacar a Herald of the Arc Light,si el jugador responde al ataque, hacer efecto de seleccionar y destruir.

VS Yummy Going 1°

Utilizar el mismo side deck, ya que Phantazmay fuerza el link del rival y puede negar, ademas nos sirve que sea dragon. 

 

VS Lunalight Going 2°

Entra: Artifact Lancea x3, Droll & Lock Bird  x3, Kaijus x2

Sale: Dracotail Pan x1, Fallen of Albaz  x1, Rahu Dracotail  x1, Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous x1 , Effect Veiler x2, Nibiru, the Primal Being x2

  • Cuando Lunalight Silver Hound si toque el cementerio, desterrarla antes de activar magicas o trampas.
  • Se puede hacer Titaniklad the Ash Dragon con Nibiru, the Primal Being o el Kaiju, para pasar por ataque a Lunalight Liger Dancer con Branded Fusion.
  • Teoricamente, se le puede tirar Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion al segundo efecto de Lunalight Masquerade. Ya que añade a la mano y es un efecto activado, sino resuelve, no puede desterrar para fusionar. Tambien se les puede tirar Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit.
  • Artifact Lancea en draw phase.
  • Droll & Lock Bird en cuanto se pueda.
  • Romper Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir con Pan
  • Negar S:P Little Knight con Mululu.
Just a fun first try at deck building

Gameplan: always pass on 4 summons with Track Maker + Red Seal/Remix on board (Quick Play for synchro 5 in end phase needed with some lines) and potentially Atrii setup in spell&trap zone for Light/Dark Chaos Angel in the opponents turn with Atrii and loudness war after quick synchro with Clip and Track Maker.

Post Side you just win if you see any Side Deck cards.

Side Patterns:

1st: side out 3 Fuwa 2 Delta 2 Droll for 3 Collapse 2 D-Barrier 1 Called by and 1 Talents

2nd: side out 1 Overtake 2-3 Centurion Cards (depends if you want the Clip Primera Line) 1 Juke Joint 1 Killer Tune Synchro for either Combination of 3 Reaper + 2 Purulia or 2 Purulia 2 Nibiru 1 Droll

Arguably you could tinker with some Super-Poly lines since it enables more Synchro Lines with Mudragon/Gurara/Secreterion/Chorozo as material

When activating Gamma or Delta you can quick synchro with Clip into Primera Primus for an additional pop and follow up + Frame Gears are still live in the next turns since Driver isn't banished.

Main Deck Engine ratios aren't fixed, i feel like you could do with 1 Juke Joint and 2 Killer Tune Synchro, maybe 3 mix and 3 reco.

A small Millennium engine grants access to board breakers, a monster negate through Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord, and/or a potential DoomZ play through The Zombie Vampire's mill effect.

If you use Wedju Temple, don't worry about having a DoomZ monster as a continuous spell because the DoomZ archetype can destroy their own cards.

Metalsilver Armor is an unusual equip spell that prevents your opponent from targeting a monster anywhere with a spell, trap, or monster effect that targets exactly 1 monster, unless it specifically targets the equipped monster. This means they can't activate cards like Infinite Impermanence, Change of Heart, or Dinowrestler Pankratops to target any monster on the field, except the monster equipped with Metalsilver Armor. They also can't target a monster in either player's graveyard with effects like D.D. Crow, the Bystials, or Monster Reborn, nor can they target a face-up monster in the banished zone with the effects of Bystial Dis Pater or Paleozoic Leanchoilia.

Lastly, Metalsilver Armor combos well with DoomZ Command "D.O.O.M.D.U.R.G.". D.O.O.M.D.U.R.G. prevents your opponent from targeting the equipped monster with card effects. Metalsilver Armor + D.O.O.M.D.U.R.G. can create a lock that prevents your opponent from targeting any monster you control with card effects.

deck_excerpt: One of my favorite decks ever made so I threw together a TCG list
deck_description:
Sideboard is almost entirely comprised of addition engine ideas
-Nemeses is obviously very common in this deck but it contradicst with Dominus and honestly I have alot of fun with this deck without them.

-Demonsmith is less common likely due to the extradeck costs but with how easy it is to make exciton at the end of your combo it only made sense to just let it branch into a free Caesar.

Have not tested Spiral too much but it should be a strong card if you aren't struggling to make boards but should probably be set if possible due to it locking Nochi and Lara out of their effects.
I don't love triple Inheritance but I just could not think of something better to play, Gold Sarc maybe?
